.* Source file: "inst_0req.html"
:h2 res=10034 x=right width=70%.Requirements
:p.
Starting with V1&per.0&per.0, XWorkplace requires at
least :hp2.OS/2 Warp 4&per.:ehp2. It will :hp1.not:ehp1. run on previous versions,
for it calls OS/2 API functions not present on OS/2
Warp 3 and before&per. 
:p.
XWorkplace is currently being developed and tested on
eComStation 1&per.0 only, but should work on Warp 4
as well&per. I do not think it relies on functionality
that is present only in newer fixpaks (especially since
the IBM source code merge with FP13), but then I didn't
test this&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "vers_1compat.html"
:h2 res=10035 x=right width=70%.Compatibility with Other Software
:p.
As you might have experienced, sometimes several WPS
enhancers don't seem to like each other too much&per.
Or maybe they do like each other, but just don't get
along&per. 
:p.
However, I have tested XWorkplace with several system
utilities that I could reach at this time (on both Warp
3 and 4), and a number of users reported other utilities
to me&per. The following programs seemed to be cooperative&colon.

:ul compact.:li.
CandyBarZ 1&per.01 / 1&per.10 :li.
CommandFolder 1&per.50 :li.
Desktop Wizard 1&per.41 (mind the notes below) :li.
DragText 2&per.5 :li.
Extended Desktop 1&per.4 :li.
FeelX (installs a WPS class) :li.
Hot Scroll 0&per.80 / 1&per.00 / 1&per.10 :li.
NPS WPS 1&per.81 / 1&per.82 (mind the notes below) :li.
Object Desktop Professional 1&per.5&per.2 / 2&per.0
(mind the notes below) :li.
WatchCat 2&per.1 (installs a WPS class) :li.
WPAnimatedMousePointer 1&per.01 :li.
X&per.file 1&per.1 / 1&per.2 :li.
X&per.it 2&per.4 / 2&per.5 
:eul.:hp2.
:p.
General note&per.:ehp2. As XWorkplace is providing more features
with every released version, chances increase that features
conflict with other parties' WPS replacement classes&per.
Depending on which software was installed first (and
thus appears first in the WPS class replacement list),
XWorkplace or the other product may not get a chance
to actually change the WPS's behavior&per. 
:p.
Moreover, since XWorkplace offers a number of features
which are also contained in other WPS packages (mostly
PM hooks), you should make sure that these features
are not enabled in several packages at the same time&per.
For example, you should not enable folder status bars
in both XWorkplace and Object Desktop, which can only
lead to problems, or activate the XWorkplace trash can
while another trash can software is also installed&per.
:hp2.
:p.
Warnings&per.:ehp2. The following list of incompatibilities
is based on reports by users of XWorkplace&per. I have
not verified these yet and include them only to save
you from trouble&per. 
:ul compact.:li.
:hp2.Object Desktop&per.:ehp2. OD manipulates the WPS just as intensively
as XWorkplace does (maybe even more), so it's just natural
that most problems have arised with this software&per.
:hp2.
:p.
Note&colon.:ehp2. I do not have Object Desktop&per. The following
is all I know&per. If you find out something, you're
welcome to tell me, and I'll add that to this section&per.
But please do not write me that OD does not cooperate
well with XWorkplace&per. :hp1.I know,:ehp1. and there's little
I can do about it&per. 
:p.
For all versions, the following rule applies&colon.
If you have trouble, XWorkplace probably conflicts with
OD's folder replacement class, TSEnhFolder&per. If nothing
else works, you can always deregister that class (using
the XWorkplace "WPS Class list" object), and you'll
probably get XWorkplace to work&per. 
:p.
But before that, mind the following notes&colon. :hp2.
:p.
All Object Desktop versions&per.:ehp2. 
:p.
I was reported that XWorkplace does not cooperate with
the :hp2."Browse mode":ehp2. feature of Object Desktop&per. You
will have to switch this feature off, sorry&per. 
:p.
Also, you should make sure to have the :hp2."Folder status
bars":ehp2. disabled in Object Desktop before enabling the
respective XWorkplace function, or the funniest things
might happen&per. 
:p.
Finally, I was reported that XFolder keeps adding status
bars to Object Desktop's :hp2."Launchpads":ehp2. even where they
don't belong&per. Apparently, these things are derived
from the WPFolder class also; they have an "XFolder"
page in their settings notebooks though, so you can
turn off XFolder's status bars for them&per. If the
object doesn't have an "XFolder" page, you can try to
manually use the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.STATUSBAR=NO:font facename=default size=0x0. folder setup string of
the XFolder class&per. :hp2.
:p.
Object Desktop 2&per.0&per.:ehp2. :link reftype=hd res=10170.Stefan Zechmeister:elink. got OD
2&per.0 to work with XWorkplace doing this&colon. 
:ol compact.:li.
Install OD 2&per.0&per. :li.
Install OD fixkit #1&per. :li.
Install XWorkplace&per. :li.
Go to the "XWorkplace Setup" object, "Paranoia" page,
and raise the "Menu item ID offset" to 700 or above&per.
Starting with V0&per.9&per.0, the default is now 700&per.

:eol.
:p.
If you then move XWorkplace's installation folder to
another folder, make sure the target folder has OD's
extra features turned off&per. Otherwise XWorkplace
will complain that its Configuration Folder does not
exist&per. 
.br
:li.
If you are using :hp2.NPS WPS,:ehp2. you must make sure to have
its "Select by name" and "Sort by extension" features
disabled, because XWorkplace offers these features also
and gets confused if these features are added by NPS
WPS also&per. 
:p.
XWorkplace does :hp1.not:ehp1. work with the automatic menu selection
of NPS WPS, at least not if you are using the "Folder
content" functions&per. This might lead to bad PM hangs&per.
Use XWorkplace's "Sliding menu" feature instead&per.

.br
:li.
I was reported that XWorkplace seems to have problems
cooperating with :hp2.Program Commander/2&per.:ehp2. Apparently,
this can be solved by switching off the "SmartIcons"
feature for title bars&per. 
.br
:li.
XWorkplace also seemed to have problems with :hp2.DragText:ehp2.
on some systems&per. There must be a setting somewhere
in that software to start DragText delayed, which should
solve this&per. 
.br
:li.
I was told by Hauke Laging that :hp2.Extended Clipboard (EClip):ehp2.
by Hinnerk Becker does not cooperate with XWorkplace&per.
On Hauke's Warp 4 system, the WPS hung at startup and
did not respond to anything&per. Hauke then told me
that the problem can be resolved by removing EClip from
the startup folder&per. (I was unable to reproduce all
this, but I'm reporting this to you anyway&per.) 
.br
:li.
Several users also reported that the "Snap to grid"
function did not seem to work&per. I have tested both
Warp 3 and 4 and encountered no problems; these users
all had some version of Object Desktop installed, so
I suspect in respect to the "Snap to grid" feature,
XWorkplace and Object Desktop seem to be colliding somehow&per.

.br
:li.
Bernd Schemmer reported that XWorkplace seems to be
using the same menu ID's as the :hp2.LAN Server GUI:ehp2.&per.
If you're using LAN Server (or other software that might
suffer from this), you can now change XWorkplace's menu
IDs in the :link reftype=hd res=10083."XWorkplace Setup":elink. object&per. The default
menu ID offset has now (V0&per.51) been raised from
100 to 300 to avoid these conflicts&per. 
.br
:li.
Michael Holzapfel reported that installing GRADD drivers
for the :hp2.ELSA Winner 2000FC:ehp2. video card crashed his system
when XWorkplace V0&per.71 was installed, causing a CHKDSK
at the next reboot, which in turn damaged the newly
installed drivers, so the system wouldn't start at all&per.
He told me that de-installing XWorkplace helped&per.

.br
:li.
Dirk Schulz reported that Desktop Wizard and XWorkplace
don't like each other too much&per. On his system, he
was able to increase the WPS's stability by de-installing
Desktop Wizard&per. Glad he didn't de-install XWorkplace&per.
;-) 
:p.
I was also reported that Prompt ver&per. 1&per.12 by
Gary L&per. Robinson, which appears to implement a subset
of the Desktop Wizard features, appears to work fine
though&per. 
:eul.
:p.

.* Source file: "inst_1inst.html"
:h2 res=10036 x=right width=70%.Installation
:p.
Before installing XWorkplace, please read the :link reftype=hd res=10035."Compatibility
with other software":elink. page in the appendices to this
reference&per. 
:p.
Starting with V0&per.9&per.0, XWorkplace is installed
using the WarpIN installer, a :link reftype=hd res=10150.Netlabs:elink. project by Jens
BÑckman and myself&per. This finally allows you to install
XWorkplace using a graphical interface and copy the
files to a target directory&per. 
:p.
Also, the way National Language Support (NLS) works
has been reconsidered&per. XWorkplace now per default
comes with English NLS&per. If you wish to install a
different language, download both the XWorkplace base
package and a second NLS package for your favorite language&per.
Install XWorkplace first, then the NLS package&per.

:p.
Then restart the WPS&per. 
:p.
After the restart, XWorkplace will automatically create
a :link reftype=hd res=10040.default configuration folder:elink.&per. If you wish to recreate
this default configuration, go to the "Objects" page
in the :link reftype=hd res=10083."XWorkplace Setup" object:elink. and press the respective
button&per. 
:p.
XFolder neither changes :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.CONFIG&per.SYS:font facename=default size=0x0. settings nor
does it copy any files into OS/2 system directories&per.
Everything XFolder needs is situated in its own directory&per.
The only things XFolder needs to work properly are a
number of settings in OS2&per.INI, which will be removed
when you uninstall XFolder&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "inst_2deinst.html"
:h2 res=10037 x=right width=70%.De-installation
:p.
There are several ways to de-install XWorkplace&per.

:ul compact.:li.
:hp2.The easy way&per.:ehp2. 
:p.
Since XWorkplace now uses WarpIN for :link reftype=hd res=10036.installation:elink., it
now uses WarpIN for de-installation also&per. Either
double-click on the WarpIN program object and select
the XWorkplace package(s) for de-installation, or double-click
on the XWorkplace archive again, both of which will
de-install XWorkplace&per. 
:eul.
:p.
In case WarpIN is unable to de-install XWorkplace (or
you don't trust WarpIN to do the job right), you can
:hp2.manually de-install XWorkplace&per.:ehp2. 
:ul compact.:li.
:hp2.The clean way&per.:ehp2. 
:p.
XWorkplace's installation is entirely based on WPS classes&per.
If you deregister all of XWorkplace's classes, you'll
get your regular OS/2 Workplace Shell back&per. You
don't have to undo any :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.CONFIG&per.SYS:font facename=default size=0x0. changes, because
there are none&per. 
:p.
However, before deregistering classes, you should undo
all of XWorkplace's class replacements&per. So this
is a two-step process (you can use the "WPS Class List"
object for this)&colon. 
.br

:ol compact.:li.
:hp2.Undo:ehp2. all the following class :hp2.replacements:ehp2. (if present)&colon.

:ul compact.:li.
XFldObject, replacing WPObject :li.
XFolder, replacing WPFolder :li.
XFldDataFile, replacing WPDataFile :li.
XFldDisk, replacing WPDisk :li.
XFldDesktop, replacing WPDesktop :li.
XWPProgramFile, replacing WPProgramFile :li.
XWPSound, replacing WPSound :li.
XWPMouse, replacing WPMouse :li.
XWPKeyboard, replacing WPKeyboard 
:eul.
:p.
:li.
:hp2.Deregister:ehp2. all the X* classes listed above&per. 
.br
:li.
In addition, :hp2.deregister:ehp2. the following (if present)&colon.

:ul compact.:li.
XFldSystem :li.
XFldWPS :li.
XFldStartup :li.
XFldShutdown :li.
XWPSetup :li.
XWPClassList :li.
XWPTrashCan :li.
XWPTrashObject 
:eul.
:p.
:li.
Then :hp2.restart the WPS&per.:ehp2. XWorkplace should be gone&per.

.br
:li.
XWorkplace has created a few sections in your OS2&per.INI
file&per. You can safely delete all sections starting
with "XWorkplace", but only do this if you're sure you
don't want to re-install XWorkplace, because all your
settings will get lost&per. 
:eol.
:p.
:li.
:hp2.The ugly way&per.:ehp2. This is the "emergency exit" in case
your computer isn't working at all any more&per. This
is not recommended and only given as a last resort&per.

.br

:ol compact.:li.
Reboot your computer and press Alt-F1 while the little
"OS/2" box is showing&per. Open a command line from
the "Recovery choices" menu&per. 
.br
:li.
From the command line, rename the XWorkplace directory
(the parent directory of the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.BIN:font facename=default size=0x0. directory with :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XFLDR&per.DLL:font facename=default size=0x0.&per.

.br
:li.
Reboot&per. When the Desktop starts up, it will not
find the XWorkplace classes (in :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XFLDR&per.DLL:font facename=default size=0x0.), because
the directory specified when registering the classes
is now invalid&per. You should get a clean WPS this
way too&per. Note however that this does not unreplace
or deregister the XWorkplace classes! 
:eol.
:p.

:eul.
:p.
If you wish to remove XWorkplace because you don't consider
it to be of any use for you, that's fine&per. 
:p.
However, if you remove it because it does not seem to
be working right or messes up your system, please :link reftype=hd res=10025.contact
the developer's team,:elink. so we can improve it&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "inst_2update.html"
:h2 res=10038 x=right width=70%.Updating from a Previous Version of XWorkplace
:p.
XWorkplace can be installed over old versions of XFolder
without any problems&per. WarpIN is capable of overwriting
files which are currently in use (as the XFolder/XWorkplace
files are by the WPS), so we have no problem there&per.

:p.
If you experience anything unexpected with your new
version of XWorkplace, please look in the :link reftype=hd res=10018."Version information":elink.
section to find out what has been added to XFolder/XWorkplace&per.

:p.
Also, it is always a good idea to read the README file
which comes with XWorkplace&per. You find that in the
main XWorkplace installation directory&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "inst_4nls.html"
:h2 res=10039 x=right width=70%.Installing National Language Support
:p.
XWorkplace is capable of supporting languages other
than English, even though per default it comes with
English National Language Support (NLS)&per. For those
languages however, you will need an :hp2.XWorkplace NLS package&per.:ehp2.
Such a package will contain only the language-specific
files for a specific languages&per. 
:p.
Please check :link reftype=hd res=10100.http&colon.//www&per.xworkplace&per.org:elink.
for available NLS packages&per. I only maintain English
myself, but I try to keep track of the translations
done by other people as time permits&per. 
:p.
Note that NLS packages are version specific&per. That
is, for a given XWorkplace version, install only a matching
NLS package, or XWorkplace might malfunction more or
less badly&per. 
:p.
NLS packages are installed using WarpIN too&per. If
you wish to use a language other than English, after
XWorkplace has been installed, do not restart your computer
yet, but install your NLS package next&per. Then restart
the WPS&per. 
:p.
When several languages are installed, the :link reftype=hd res=10082."XWorkplace
Setup" object:elink. offers you a "Language" drop-down box
to change the current language&per. 
.br

