:h2 res=10040 x=right width=70%.Default Additions to the Context Menus
:p.
:hp2.Class&colon. XFolder:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.

:p.
The XFolder WPS class enables you to freely add new
items to the context menu of all folders on your system&per.

:p.
Here's a screenshot for the preset XFolder configuration
(as defined by the install script)&colon. 
:artwork name='menu1.bmp' align=left.
:p.
You will see the same new popup items on all folders
on your system&per. What happens now if you press one
of the items in the submenu is that XFolder performs
the selected action on just the folder that the context
menu was opened for&per. 
:p.
For example, if you select :hp2."OS/2 window":ehp2. from the :hp2."Command
lines":ehp2. submenu, an OS/2 window will be opened, but the
path will already have changed to that of the folder
whose context menu was opened&per. 
:p.
For detailed help about the default context menu extensions,
select one of the new menu items and press "F1" while
mouse button 1 is still down&per. This will explain
that very menu item&per. 
:p.
XFolder allows you to freely modify these all these
context menu items&per. See :link reftype=hd res=10042."Configuring context menus":elink.
for details&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "menu_2template.html"
:h2 res=10041 x=right width=70%.Creating Objects with XFolder
:p.
:hp2.Class&colon. XFolder:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
In the default configuration, the :hp2."Create another":ehp2. context
submenu contains items for creating Desktop objects&per.
By selecting one of the items in this submenu, XFolder
will create a new object in the folder whose context
menu was used&per. 
:p.
Per default, if the folder is open, XFolder will make
the title of the new object editable, just as if you
had clicked on it with the Alt key pressed&colon. 
.br

:artwork name='titleedit.bmp' runin align=left.
:p.
However, if you hold down the :hp2.Shift key:ehp2. while selecting
the menu item, XFolder will automatically open the Settings
notebook of the new object after creation&per. 
:p.
You can change this behavior on the "Context menus"
pages in the new :link reftype=hd res=10083."Workplace Shell":elink. object&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "menu_3config.html"
:h2 res=10042 x=right width=70%.Configuring Context Menus
:p.
:hp2.Class&colon. XFolder:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
What makes XFolder different from other folder enhancements
is that you can :hp1.freely configure:ehp1. popup menus without
having to reboot&per. 
:p.
This is done with the use of a separate :hp2.Configuration
Folder,:ehp2. which looks just like any normal WPS folder&per.
The installation script placed it in the "XWorkplace"
folder on your Desktop, but you may move it anywhere
you like&per. 
:p.
Whatever you put into this configuration folder will
immediately appear in the context menus of all the folders
on your system&per. 
:p.
Let's clarify this by taking a look at the pre-set configuration
again&colon. 
:artwork name='menu1.bmp' align=left.
:p.
The pre-set configuration folder looks like this&colon.

:artwork name='menu2.bmp' align=left.
:p.
As you can see, the folders and program objects in the
XFolder Configuration folder correspond to the items
in the context menu&per. So if you add something to
the Configuration Folder or remove some object from
it, this will immediately affect all folder context
menus&per. 
:p.
However, the action which XFolder performs upon selecting
a context menu items depends on the type of object that
corresponds to the menu item&per. For details about
how this works, please go to the XWorkplace installation
folder and select "Help" for the Configuration Folder
which you will find there&per. 
:p.
As simple it may seem, the combined folder/object approach
of the XFolder configuration folder is very powerful&per.
You can add all your favorite programs, templates, and
data files here which make sense to be executed in any
directory&per. 
:p.
If you know how to program REXX, you're even better
off&colon. you can write your own scripts that manipulate
the WPS, create program objects for them and put these
in the configuration folders&per. On the :link reftype=hd res=10016."Frequently
Asked Questions":elink. page, you can find out more about this&per.

.br

.* Source file: "menu_5order.html"
:h2 res=10043 x=right width=70%.The Order of Menu Items
:p.
:hp2.Class&colon. XFolder:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
Since V0&per.60 you may (finally) change the order of
menu items within a context menu or one of its submenus&per.
(Previously, this was really tiresome to accomplish&per.)

:p.
Simply open the XFolder Configuration Folder or one
of its subfolders 
:ul compact.:li.
either in :hp2.Details:ehp2. view 
.br
:li.
or in :hp2.Icon:ehp2. view&per. 
:p.
However, this does not work if the Icon view has the
icons ordered "as placed"&per. The icon view needs to
be in "flowed" (single column) or "non-flowed" (multiple
columns) mode&per. The default configuration folders
have this enabled by default, but this can be set manually
on the "View" page in each folder's settings notebook&per.
(This is more quickly to accomplish with the XFolder
"Small icons in icon and tree views" menu items, by
the way&per.) 
:eul.
:p.
If you now change the order of the objects in this folder
with the mouse (drag and drop) :hp2.and then:ehp2. close this configuration
folder, you will see that the order of menu items has
changed accordingly&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "menu_6favorite.html"
:h2 res=10044 x=right width=70%.The "Folder Content" Functions
:p.
:hp2.Class&colon. XFolder:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
XFolder offers you to view the contents of folders from
the context menus without having to open them&per. This
can be very handy if you need to open a single file
from a folder, but you do not want to open a dozen folders
in order to reach it&per. 
:p.
Here's an example (the "XFolder" development directory
from the author's harddisk)&colon. 
:artwork name='favorite.bmp' align=left.
:p.
As you can see, the content of the "XFolder" folder
is displayed; the subfolders in this folders lead to
subsequent submenus&per. 
:p.
The "Folder content" menus behave just like the WarpCenter's
do&colon. if you click on an item, its default view
will be opened&per. If you click on a folder menu item,
another submenu with the contents of this folder will
be opened; if you click on it with mouse button 2, the
WPS folder will be opened as a window instead&per. 
:p.
The "Folder content" functions are used in two different
contexts&colon. 
:ul compact.:li.
For one, you can decide to always have the contents
of the folder whose context menu you have opened displayed
in this very context menu&per. The respective context
menu item is then called "Folder contents" (how surprising)&per.
As a result, the "Folder contents" menu is different
for each context menu&per. 
:p.
In the above screenshot, this can be seen with the "Ordnerinhalt"
menu item (which is German for :hp2."Folder content";:ehp2. sorry,
I was just too lazy to do a second screenshot)&per.

:p.
The folder content menus can be switched on and off
on the "Context menus" page in the new :link reftype=hd res=10083."Workplace Shell"
object:elink.&per. 
.br
:li.
Second, you can declare a certain folder to be one of
your :hp2."favorite" folders&per.:ehp2. This can be done on the
"XFolder" page in every folder's Settings notebook&per.
All "favorite" folders will be displayed in all context
menus; you can, for example, switch this feature on
for the Desktop, and you will be able to reach the Desktop
and everything that resides on and below its folder
hierarchy from all context menus&per. (This works for
the Drives folder also, by the way&per.) 
:p.
In the above screenshot, the "frequent" menu item is
a folder on my Desktop in which I put things I access
frequently&per. I have declared this folder to be my
only "favorite" folder, so everything I put in this
folder will appear in all context menus&per. 
:eul.
:p.

.* Source file: "menu_7selectsome.html"
:h2 res=10045 x=right width=70%."Select by name"
:p.
:hp2.Class&colon. XFolder:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
XFolder allows you to select only some objects in a
folder according to a typical specification&per. 
:p.
This is done by using the "Select by name" menu item,
which resides in the "Select" menu on Warp 3; on Warp
4, this menu item can be found in the "View" menu&per.

:p.
You then get a dialog window where you may enter a file
specification such as :font facename='Courier' size=18x12."*&per.txt":font facename=default size=0x0. and select or deselect
files according to this specification&per. 
:p.
Per default, XFolder also defines :link reftype=hd res=10053.Ctrl+S:elink. as a :link reftype=hd res=10053.folder
hotkey:elink. for this function&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "menu_8snaptogrid.html"
:h2 res=10046 x=right width=70%.The "Snap to Grid" Feature
:p.
:hp2.Class&colon. XFolder:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
XFolder can add a "Snap to grid" menu item to all folder
context menus&per. When selecting it, all objects in
the folder will "jump" onto an invisible grid&per. 
:p.
The "Snap to grid" feature is a bit hard to explain&per.
Just think of a folder whose objects are pretty messed
up&colon. how many times have you found yourself trying
to align those objects below or next to each other?

.br

:artwork name='snap1.bmp' runin align=left.
:p.
The "Arrange" menu item doesn't help here, since it
reorders the objects completely&per. Now imagine a set
of invisible equidistant lines spread over the folder
window, which attract the objects therein when you select
"Snap to grid"&per. 
.br

:artwork name='snap2.bmp' runin align=left.
:p.
The "Snap to grid" menu item will only be visible when
the following applies&colon. 
:ol compact.:li.
the folder must be open; 
.br
:li.
the folder must have the no-grid icon view (the default
for most folders); it will not be visible for folders
in details or tree view or if you have changed the icon
view to "flowed" or "non-flowed" in the folder's settings
dialog; 
.br
:li.
the folder must not have the "Always maintain sort order"
setting enabled&per. 
:eol.
:p.
You can specify the grid's origin and spacing on the
"Grid" page in the new :link reftype=hd res=10083."Workplace Shell" object:elink.&per.
:hp2.
:p.
Note&colon.:ehp2. With V0&per.81, the "Snap to grid" behavior
has changed slightly&per. Per default, XFolder will
only let the currently :hp2.selected:ehp2. objects snap on the
grid&per. However, if you hold down the :hp2.Shift:ehp2. key while
selecting that menu item, all items will be snapped
(like in previous versions)&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "menu_91copyfilename.html"
:h2 res=10047 x=right width=70%.The "Copy Filename" Feature
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XFldDataFile, XFolder:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
XWorkplace can copy the filename of any file into the
clipboard after you select "Copy filename" from the
object's context menu&per. Note that this applies to
all file-system objects, not just folders; however,
this does not apply to abstract Desktop objects (shadows,
program objects etc&per.), because these just don't
have a filename&per. 
:artwork name='copyfilename.bmp' align=left.
:p.
If you select "Copy filename" :hp1.without:ehp1. holding down the
:hp2."Shift" key,:ehp2. XWorkplace will only copy the filename
itself&per. 
:p.
If you hold down the "Shift" key while selecting "Copy
filename", XWorkplace will copy the fully qualified
filename, i&per.e&per. the drive letter, the path and
the filename itself&per. 
:p.
Assuming that the folder in the above screenshot resides
on the Desktop, "Copy filename" would copy :font facename='Courier' size=18x12."C&colon.\Desktop\Folder":font facename=default size=0x0.
into the clipboard, if you hold down the "Shift" key,
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12."Folder":font facename=default size=0x0. otherwise&per. 
:p.
This now (V0&per.80) also works when you have more than
one object selected in the folder&per. In this case,
the filenames of the selected objects are all copied
to the clipboard, separated by spaces&per. 
:p.
XWorkplace also defines Ctrl+Insert as a default :link reftype=hd res=10053.folder
hotkey:elink. for copying the filename(s) of the currently
selected object(s)&per. 
:p.
You can disable the menu item and change the hotkey(s)
in the :link reftype=hd res=10083.Global Settings:elink.&per. 
.br

