.* Source file: "fldr_30turbo.html"
:h2 res=10049 x=right width=70%.Turbo Folders
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XFolder, XWPFileSystem, XFldDataFile,
XWPProgram, XWPProgramFile:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
"Turbo folders" are a shorthand name for a large number
of enhancements to the internal handling of folder contents
in the Workplace Shell&per. In short, opening folders
with lots of files in them will become :hp1.significantly:ehp1.
faster&per. 
:p.
For safety, turbo folders are disabled by default&per.
You can turn them on in the :link reftype=hd res=10083."XWorkplace Setup" object:elink.&per.

:p.
The speed enhancements provided with folder populating
are described on this page&per. Note that starting with
V1&per.0&per.1, when you enable turbo folders, extended
associations are enabled automatically as well&per.
As it has turned out, enabling only one of them made
the WPS quite unstable&per. See :link reftype=hd res=10060.Extended file associations:elink.
for a detailed description of that feature&per. :hp2.
:p.
Short description:ehp2. 
:p.
When a folder is first opened in the WPS, it is "populated"
-- which means that all the files are collected from
the directory that is represented by the folder&per.
As you will know, the WPS is not good at handling large
amounts of files&per. Opening folders with many objects
(say, a thousand files or more) can hog the system for
minutes&per. 
:p.
"Turbo folders" can partly fix this problem&per. Below
is a benchmark comparison for some pathological folders
with the time in seconds that populating these folders
has taken on my system&per. This benchmark only shows
the time that invoking the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.QUICKOPEN=IMMEDIATE:font facename=default size=0x0. XFolder
setup string has consumed&per. As usual, your results
may vary, depending on the speed of your hard disks
and processor(s)&per. 
:cgraphic.
                        turbo off       turbo on

    JFS folder with       160 s           53 s
    10,000 files

    JFS folder with       211 s           60 s
    13,000 files

    HPFS folder with                      56 s
    10,000 files

:ecgraphic.
:p.
Apparently the time the WPS normally takes for populating
folders increases exponentially with the number of files
in the folder&per. :hp2.
:p.
Detailed description:ehp2. 
:p.
Essentially, the "turbo folders" feature is a full rewrite
of the folder populate code&per. XWorkplace uses the
following techniques to make this a lot faster&colon.

:ul compact.:li.
Each folder now has a binary balanced tree containing
all the objects that have been added to the folder's
internal content list so far&per. For file-system objects,
this tree is sorted by the objects' short real names&per.
This makes it much more efficient to find out if the
object is already in the tree or still needs to be added&per.
I assume that the original checkup code in the WPS is
responsible for the enourmous delays with large amounts
of files&per. 
.br
:li.
Instead of only one extra thread, "turbo folders" will
start two extra threads for populating a folder&per.
One is reponsible for collecting file data from the
disk (via the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DosFindFirst:font facename=default size=0x0. and :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DosFindNext:font facename=default size=0x0. system APIs),
and the other one is responsible for checking whether
the object is already awake and creating a new object,
if necessary&per. 
:p.
Depending on the file system, the above two APIs can
be quite slow when extended attributes have to be collected
(as is the case with the WPS)&per. While this happens,
the calling thread is blocked, doing nothing but waiting
for data from the hard disk to arrive&per. This idle
time can now be used by the other thread for creating
the object in memory, which can be quite time consuming
as well&per. 
:p.
In addition, using two threads will scale better on
multi-processor (SMP) systems&per. 
:p.
The above two techniques together made folder populating
so much faster&per. The time that is now needed for
populating the folder roughly equates the time that
the system spends in the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DosFindFirst:font facename=default size=0x0. and :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DosFindNext:font facename=default size=0x0.
system APIs, so I do not think this can be sped up much
more (unless somebody manages to make these system APIs
more efficient)&per. 
.br
:li.
"Turbo folders" also completely replaces the icon loading
for executable files&per. As you will know, if you open
a folder with &per.EXE files, the WPS will attempt to
find an icon in the executable and, if one is found,
use it for the object&per. Program and data file objects
will also load icons from executables&per. 
:p.
The WPS code for loading icons suffers from several
limitations&per. Most importantly, it appears to be
slow&per. This code has also been totally replaced in
XWorkplace&per. 
:p.
In addition, the WPS does not appear to share icons
much in the WPS&per. XWorkplace will also attempt to
reuse icons as much as possible to avoid the need to
reload them from the executables all the time&per. 
:p.
Essentially I am no longer allowing the WPS to read
executable icons at all, but will only use my own code
for now&per. This works for LX and Win16 and OS/2 NE
executables&per. Win32 PE resources (as used by most
executables under Windows 95 or newer) are presently
not understood; PE files will receive a dull default
icon, but at least the WPS will no longer hang forever
with them&per. 
:p.
As one side effect, this will change the behavior for
Win16 icons if the system icon size is 40x40; instead
of scaling, XWorkplace will now center the 32x32 icon&per.

:eul.
:p.

.* Source file: "fldr_38sort.html"
:h2 res=10050 x=right width=70%.Extended Sort Options
:p.
:hp2.Class&colon. XFolder:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
XWorkplace can also enhance the "Sort" functions of
the Workplace Shell&per. :hp2.
:p.
Important note&colon.:ehp2. In order to avoid confusion, the
sort extensions are disabled by default&per. You can
enable them in the :link reftype=hd res=10083."XWorkplace Setup" object:elink.&per. 
:p.
The new XWorkplace sort features are&colon. 
:ul compact.:li.
Finally, there are :hp2.global sort settings,:ehp2. which previously
did not exist in the WPS&per. While it was possible
to set a number of folder settings globally, until now
sorting could only be influenced for each individual
folder, which was quite annoying&per. XWorkplace introduces
a "Sort" page to the :link reftype=hd res=10083."Workplace Shell" object:elink. for global
sort settings, which can be overridden individually
for each folder&per. 
.br
:li.
XWorkplace also gets rid of some of the strange sort
settings which nobody used anyway, such as the "sort
class"&per. (This setting did not make much sense, because
WPFolder is the only class which introduces meaningful
sort criteria anyway&per.) 
.br
:li.
Most importantly, XWorkplace gives you lots of new sort
options for folders -- both for each individual folder
and globally through the "Sort" page in the :link reftype=hd res=10083."Workplace
Shell" object:elink.&per. 
:p.
For one, :hp2.new sort criteria:ehp2. such as "object class" and
"file name extension" have been introduced&per. 
:p.
Secondly, there is now a new "super-criterion" for always
:hp2.sorting folders first,:ehp2. in addition to the folder's default
sort criterion&per. For example, you can sort by size
and still have all folders sorted to the top&per. 
:p.
For all this, the :hp2."Sort" submenu:ehp2. in each folder context
menu has been reworked too&colon. 
:artwork name='sort.bmp' align=left.
.br
As you can see, XWorkplace adds menu items for "Always
maintain sort order" and "Sort folders first" for quick
access&per. 
:p.
In addition, you can quickly change the default sort
criterion for a certain folder by :hp2.holding down the "Shift":ehp2.
key while selecting a sort criterion in the "Sort" menu&per.

:eul.
:p.
XWorkplace also defines :link reftype=hd res=10053.folder hotkeys:elink. for the most
frequently used sort criteria&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "fldr_4treeviews.html"
:h2 res=10051 x=right width=70%.Auto-Scroll Tree Views
:p.
:hp2.Class&colon. XFolder:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
XFolder can monitor open Tree views of folders and automatically
scroll down the folder window if necessary&per. 
:p.
You have probably encountered this situation a zillion
times&colon. you wish to expand a tree of a folder Tree
view which is visible at the bottom of the folder window&per.

.br

:artwork name='intro_4treeviews1.bmp' runin align=left.
:p.
Normally, if you click on the "plus" sign next to the
"dll" directory, the tree will expand, but you will
not be able to see its contents&per. This default OS/2
behavior is really tiresome, because almost every other
time that a Tree view is expanded, you'll have to scroll
down manually to actually see the contained objects&per.

:p.
XFolder will now :hp1.automatically:ehp1. scroll down the folder
window if the newly appearing items begin to appear
outside the currently visible window area&colon. 
.br

:artwork name='intro_4treeviews2.bmp' runin align=left.
:p.
XFolder does this by internally monitoring the Tree
view in the background after you click on the "plus"
sign and then, as soon as the WPS is done populating
the folder, automatically scrolls down&per. This "monitoring"
does not cause an additional CPU load, because XFolder
simply intercepts a single window notification message
internally&per. (For this reason it is totally inconceivable
that IBM has not implemented this behavior already&per.)

:p.
XFolder will make the bottom-most item that was displayed
visible, unless the tree below the folder you clicked
on contains too many items to fit into the window&per.
In this case, XFolder will scroll the item which you
expanded to the very top of the visible window area&per.

:p.
It is probably the best thing to try out this function
yourself, in order to get used to it&per. The OS/2 directory
is a good candidate for this&per. Although this behavior
might be a bit irritating at first, I'm sure that after
a while, you'll probably don't want to miss it&per.

:p.
You can still disable this feature in the :link reftype=hd res=10083.Global Settings:elink.&per.

.br

.* Source file: "fldr_5quickopen.html"
:h2 res=10052 x=right width=70%."Quick Open" Folders
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XFldObject, XFolder:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
You can tell XWorkplace to prepare certain folders to
display their contents more quickly when you open them&per.
After the WPS has booted, XWorkplace will go through
all folders which have this feature enabled and read
in their contents&per. If you then open one of these
folders, its contents will be displayed almost immediately&per.

:p.
In order to enable this feature, open the Settings notebook
for the folder for which you wish to enable this feature&per.
On the "XFolder" page therein, check the "QuickOpen"
flag&per. 
:p.
After the next Desktop startup, XWorkplace will then
read in the contents of that folder and load all the
icons&per. Note that XWorkplace only does this right
after the WPS has booted, so changing the "QuickOpen"
flag of a folder has no immediate effect&per. 
:p.
Depending on how many folders have the "QuickOpen" flag
set, Desktop startup might take quite a while&per. Reading
all the icons does not become faster by using this feature&per.
The only difference is that the icons are read earlier&per.

.br

.* Source file: "fldr_5xelerators.html"
:h2 res=10053 x=right width=70%.Folder Hotkeys
:p.
:hp2.Class&colon. XFolder:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
XFolder can add new keyboard accelerators (or hotkeys,
or shortcuts, whatever terminology you prefer&per.&per.&per.)
for use within folders&per. Note that these keys ONLY
work when a folder has the focus&per. They do not work
when any other window is currently active&per. 
:p.
All the following keys are just shortcuts to certain
menu items&per. 
:p.
The default configuration adds the following keys for
use within folders&colon. 
:ul compact.:li.
:hp2.F5:ehp2. will refresh the folder contents&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.Ctrl+A:ehp2. will select all objects in the folder&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.Ctrl+D:ehp2. will de-select all objects in the folder&per.

.br
:li.
:hp2.Ctrl+S:ehp2. will :link reftype=hd res=10045.select objects by name:elink.&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.Ctrl+N:ehp2. will sort the folder contents by name&per. 
.br
:li.
