status bars (in my view, that is)&per. These are highly
configurable on the "Status bars" pages in the new :link reftype=hd res=10083."Workplace
Shell" object:elink. and can also be switched on and off :link reftype=hd res=10055.individually:elink.
for each folder&per. :hp2.
:p.
Note&colon.:ehp2. Folder status bars are disabled per default
to prevent side-effects in case you already have software
which adds folder status bars&per. Go to the :link reftype=hd res=10083."Workplace
Shell" object:elink. to turn the XFolder status bars on, but
make sure to disable this feature in other software
first; otherwise results are unpredictable&per. 
:artwork name='intro_4statusbars.bmp' align=left.
:p.
Status bars operate in :hp2.three modes,:ehp2. that is, they can
display different information depending on how many
objects are currently selected in the folder container&colon.

:ul compact.:li.
"No-objects mode"&colon. this applies when no object
is selected at all&per. Per default, this displays the
total number of objects in the folder and their total
size as well as the free space on the folder's drive&per.

.br
:li.
"One-object mode"&colon. this applies when exactly one
object is selected&per. Depending on the class of the
object, different information is displayed&per. For
example, folders and data files will display file system
information (real name, class, size, date, and time)&per.

.br
:li.
"Multiple-objects mode"&colon. this applies when more
than one object is selected&per. Per default, this displays
the number of selected items, the total number of objects
in the folder and the added size of the selected items
(as in the above screenshot)&per. 
:eul.
:p.
For each of these three modes you may :hp2.configure:ehp2. freely
what will be displayed in the status bars&per. This
is explained in detail on the :link reftype=hd res=10058."Configuring status bars":elink.
page&per. 
.br

