.* Source file: "file_0intro.html"
:h2 res=10059 x=right width=70%.Introduction
:p.
XWorkplace can enhance some the Workplace Shell's file
operations&per. Since file operations are really what
a shell is supposed to be doing in the first place,
this is one of the main areas I am currently working
on&per. 
:p.
Unfortunately, this has proven to be the most difficult,
shaky, and obscure part of the WPS&per. The WPS is extremely
multithreaded, and IBM hasn't cared to document exactly
those interfaces which control the various file threads&per.

:p.
There are a few things which I have found anyway, even
though IBM didn't want me to, so here we go&per. :hp2.
:p.
Note&colon.:ehp2. As usual, all file operation enhancements
are disabled per default in order to avoid confusion&per.
Go to the "Features" page in the :link reftype=hd res=10083."XWorkplace Setup"
object:elink. and check the flags in the "File operations"
tree to enable the various features&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "file_1extassocs.html"
:h2 res=10060 x=right width=70%.Extended File Associations
:p.
XWorkplace can replace the default Workplace Shell file
associations mechanism&per. To use them, enable the
:link reftype=hd res=10049."Turbo folders":elink. feature on the "Features" page of the
:link reftype=hd res=10083."XWorkplace Setup":elink. object&per. 
:p.
As you probably know, per default the WPS associates
programs to data files using two mechanisms&colon. "associations
by file type" and "associations by file filter"&per.

:p.
If XWorkplace's extended file associations are enabled,
you will :hp1.only:ehp1. have associations by file type&per. :hp1.
:p.
However,:ehp1. since most files do not have an explicit file
type set (which can be done on the "Type" page in a
file's settings notebook), XWorkplace will automatically
assign file types to file objects according to file
filters&per. This way you get the best of both worlds
(file types and file filters) in a more logical way&per.

:p.
So what is this good for? 
:p.
For one, I have found the standard WPS association mechanism
slightly awkward if associations are added according
to both file filters and file types&per. The new approach
is more logical in this sense&per. 
:p.
Secondly, and most importantly, XWorkplace allows you
to define :hp2.file type hierarchies&per.:ehp2. For example, there
are many file types which are really "plain text" files
also (for example, "C Code" or "HTML" files), so any
editor which can read "plain text" should be able to
read those file types also&per. 
:p.
Until now, you had to associate the same editor to all
those file types&per. With XWorkplace, you can now define
any type to be a "sub-type" of "plain text", and that
sub-type will :hp2.inherit:ehp2. the associations defined for the
parent type&per. 
:p.
This can be done on the new "File types" page in the
:link reftype=hd res=10083."Workplace Shell" object:elink. (if extended associations have
been enabled)&colon. 
:artwork name='filetypes.bmp' align=left.
:p.
To define file type hierarchies, simply :hp2.drag and drop:ehp2.
the file types in the "File types" tree onto another
file type&per. XWorkplace allows you to :hp2.import:ehp2. your
old file filters into the new associations&per. To do
this, right-click into the "Filters" field and select
"Import"&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "file_2trashcan.html"
:h2 res=10061 x=right width=70%.The XWorkplace Trash Can
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XFldObject, XWPTrashCan, XWPTrashObject:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
Starting with V0&per.9&per.0, XWorkplace introduces
a trash can too&per. 
:artwork name='file_2trashcan.bmp' runin align=left.
:p.
Most people are probably familiar with this feature,
because the MacOS, Windows 95 and KDE (on Linux) offer
this feature as well&per. Basically, the trash can temporarily
stores all the objects that have been deleted on the
system, so you can get them back in case you have accidentally
deleted something by opening the trash can (which behaves
like any folder) and restoring an object&per. 
:p.
With XWorkplace, the trash can will intercept all WPS
"delete" operations&per. (It will :hp1.not:ehp1. intercept command
line operations or the OS/2 :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DELDIR:font facename=default size=0x0. setting&per.) :hp2.
:p.
Note&colon.:ehp2. The trash can is not automatically created
during installation, and trash can "delete" support
is initially disabled to avoid confusion&per. For the
trash can to work, enable it on the "Features" page
in the :link reftype=hd res=10083."XWorkplace Setup" object&per.:elink. :hp2.
:p.
Deleting:ehp2. an object into the trash can be done in two
ways&colon. 
:ol compact.:li.
:hp2.Drag and drop:ehp2. the object(s) onto the trash can icon
or into an open trash can view&per. 
.br
:li.
XWorkplace can also intercept the :hp2.WPS "Delete" commands&per.:ehp2.
This applies to the menu item in each object's context
menu as well as the "Delete" key when it's pressed in
a folder window&per. Both actions will then move the
selected objects into the trash can first instead of
really deleting them&per. 
:p.
You can still perform a "true" delete (that is, really
delete the object, instead of moving it into the trash
can) by holding down the "Shift" key while clicking
on the "Delete" menu item in an object's context menu

:eol.
:p.
Once the objects are in the trash can, you can either
have them :hp2.destroyed:ehp2. (which will really delete the object)
or :hp2.restored:ehp2. (which will put the object back to the location
where it was deleted from)&per. 
:artwork name='trashcan.bmp' align=left.
:p.
Also, when any objects are in the trash can, the trash
can object itself has an additional menu item called
:hp2."Empty trash can":ehp2., which will delete :hp1.all:ehp1. the objects
in the trash can for good&per. 
:p.
The trash can has a new settings page in its settings
notebook, with additional features&per. Press :hp2."Help":ehp2.
on that page for more information&per. 
:p.
If you're interested in details about how the trash
can works internally, please see the :link reftype=hd res=10129.respective page:elink.
in the "XWorkplace Internals" section&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "file_3delete.html"
:h2 res=10062 x=right width=70%.Replacing "True Delete"
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XFldObject:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
Starting with V0&per.9&per.3, XWorkplace can replace
the regular "delete" mechanism of the Workplace Shell
as well&per. I call this "true delete", as opposed to
moving objects into the trash can&per. "True delete"
will immediately destroy the objects with no chance
to recover&per. 
:p.
"True delete" can be replaced by enabling the respective
setting on the "Features" page in the :link reftype=hd res=10083."XWorkplace Setup"
object&per.:elink. This is also initially disabled&per. 
:p.
Compared to the WPS's delete operations, XWorkplace's
"true delete" has a number of advantages&per. For one,
you get a proper progress bar which shows you the progress
of the delete operation&per. Secondly, when you delete
a folder with many sub-objects, you finally get a change
to cancel deletion, which isn't possible with the WPS&per.
I've had this a number of times&per.&per.&per. pressing
the "Delete" key over a folder by accident, and 100
MB of files got deleted, with no chance to interrupt&per.
Not a good idea&per. 
:p.
If "true delete" is replaced, the following actions
will be taken over by XWorkplace&colon. 
:ul compact.:li.
If the XWorkplace trash can is enabled, all regular
"delete" operations will still go to the trash can (as
described on the :link reftype=hd res=10061.previous page:elink.), so these operations
won't be affected&per. 
:p.
This will however affect "true delete" from a context
menu (if you hold down the "Shift" key while clicking
on a "Delete" context menu item) and the "Destroy object"
and "Empty trashcan" commands in the trash can itself&per.

.br
:li.
If the XWorkplace trash can is not enabled, this will
affect all WPS delete operations (i&per.e&per. every
"Delete" context menu item and "Delete" key press)&per.

:eul.
:p.

.* Source file: "file_8autorefresh.html"
:h2 res=10063 x=right width=70%.Replacing Folder Auto-Refresh
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XFldObject, XFolder:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
Starting with V0&per.9&per.9, XWorkplace can replace
the Workplace Shell's folder auto-refresh mechanism&per.

:p.
You are probably familiar with this feature of the Workplace
Shell&per. If you have a folder open and manipulate
files in that folder from the command line, you will
see that the WPS magically will know about these modifications
and refresh the folder automatically&per. 
:p.
While this is a great feature in theory, there are severe
limitations with the standard implementation of this
in the WPS&per. Most importantly, the WPS will create
excessive file-system handles for all objects that are
auto-refreshed, which will unnecessarily blow up your
INI files&per. Note that this even happens if you have
the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.AUTOREFRESHFOLDERS=NO:font facename=default size=0x0. setting in your :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.CONFIG&per.SYS:font facename=default size=0x0.
file&per. 
:p.
XWorkplace can now replace this entire mechanism if
you have enabled this replacement on the "Features"
page in the :link reftype=hd res=10083."XWorkplace Setup" object&per.:elink. 
:p.
If the replacement is enabled, XWorkplace will prevent
the internal WPS threads which are responsible for folder
auto-refresh from running&per. Among other things, this
will prevent file-system handles from being created&per.
Instead, XWorkplace will start its own threads which
will start monitoring file-system activity and automatically
refresh folders then&per. 
:p.
Note that as a result, enabling or disabling the replacement
requires a Desktop restart because XWorkplace can only
do this replacement while the WPS is starting up&per.

:p.
However, once the replacement has been enabled and the
WPS has been restarted, you can enable and disable folder
auto-refresh on the "View" page in the "Workplace Shell"
object without having to restart the WPS&per. 
.br

