.* Source file: "xsd_01intro.html"
:h2 res=10064 x=right width=70%.Introduction
:p.
XWorkplace offers you a variety of enhancements to the
Desktop startup and shutdown processes&per. This is
explained in detail on the following pages&per. :hp2.
:p.
Notes&colon.:ehp2. 
:ol compact.:li.
All these features are disabled per default and have
to be enabled individually on the "Features" page of
the :link reftype=hd res=10083."XWorkplace Setup":elink. object&per. In order to implement
these features, quite a number of changes had to be
made to some core functions of the Workplace Shell&per.
So if something is not working right, you can selectively
enable/disable each feature&per. 
.br
:li.
XWorkplace now has a :hp2."Startup panic" dialog:ehp2. which is
displayed if you hold down the :hp2."Shift" key:ehp2. while the
WPS is starting up&per. 
:p.
So if you enable some startup feature and your WPS hangs
at startup, press Ctrl+Alt+Del and hold down the "Shift"
key when the system switches to graphics mode until
the dialog appears&per. 
:p.
This dialog allows you to temporarily disable certain
XWorkplace startup features and then continue booting&per.
This will not change the XWorkplace global settings,
but only skip certain functions during startup&per.
You can then change the respective XWorkplace settings
after the system has started&per. 
:eol.
:p.

.* Source file: "xsd_02archives.html"
:h2 res=10065 x=right width=70%.WPS Archiving
:p.
:hp2.Class&colon. XFldObject, XFldDesktop:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
Starting with V0&per.9&per.0, XWorkplace offers you
an enhanced interface to the WPS archiving feature which
had been introduced with OS/2 Warp 3&per. The new functionality
is similar to that of the WPSArcO package and has been
kindly provided by that software's author, Stefan Milcke&per.

:p.
The new functionality can be :hp2.configured:ehp2. on the "Archives"
page in the Desktop's settings notebook, which is replaced
by XWorkplace&per. 
:p.
Basically, instead of just letting you decide whether
the WPS should :hp1.always:ehp1. be archived at Desktop startup,
XWorkplace now offers you much more flexible criteria
for whether the WPS should be backed up&per. 
:p.
The archives format itself is not changed&per. You can
therefore still press Alt+F1 when OS/2 is starting to
restore your backups&per. The new features only deal
with :hp1.whether:ehp1. the WPS should be backed up&per. 
:p.
When the WPS is starting up and XWorkplace is thus loaded
too, it now checks the system configuration according
to the settings which you have specified&per. If it
turns out that the WPS needs to be archived according
to your settings, archiving is turned on, the WPS continues
booting, and the WPS will then back up your Desktop&per.

:p.
You can, for example, specify that the WPS should be
backed up every so-and-so days or based on a certain
percentage that the INI files have changed&per. 
:p.
The archiving criteria are described in detail when
you press "Help" on the new "Archives" page in the Desktop's
settings notebook&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "xsd_03bootlogo.html"
:h2 res=10066 x=right width=70%.WPS Boot Logos
:p.
:hp2.Class&colon. XFldObject:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
XFolder 0&per.85 introduced the possibility to display
a user-defined bitmap during Desktop startup&per. With
XWorkplace 0&per.9&per.0, a new "Startup" page was introduced
to the Desktop's settings notebook to allow for easy
configuration of this feature&per. 
:p.
The boot logo will remain visible until the WPS has
completely initialized itself&per. It will then disappear
and no longer consume any system resources&per. 
:p.
The :hp2."Startup" page in the Desktop's settings notebook:ehp2.
allows you to define the boot logo bitmap and style&per.
More information can be obtained by pressing the "Help"
button on that page&per. 
:p.
I have included three boot logos with XWorkplace&colon.

:ul compact.:li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.xfolder&per.bmp:font facename=default size=0x0. (which will be used per default) is
a variation of the old XFolder logo&per. This should
still be handled by weaker systems too&per. :li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.os2warpx&per.bmp:font facename=default size=0x0. is an alternative, new design, which
I like much better, which however might take too long
to display on weaker systems&per. On my Pentium-133,
this one takes about two seconds to display&per. :li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.penguin&per.bmp:font facename=default size=0x0. is new with V0&per.9&per.0&per. This
is the well-known Linux penguin with an OS/2 logo on
its belly&per. 
:eul.
:p.
When :hp2.using your own bitmaps,:ehp2. mind these important notes&colon.

:ol compact.:li.
The boot logo must be an :hp2.uncompressed OS/2 1&per.3 bitmap:ehp2.
file&per. V2&per.0 bitmaps won't be loaded&per. I had
to include my own bitmap loading code because at the
time of Desktop startup, the WPS's multimedia classes
don't work yet&per. You can use PMView or the WPS multimedia
classes to convert existing files to 1&per.3 format&per.

.br
:li.
Transparency is calculated according to the most lower-left
corner pixel of the bitmap&per. That is, all pixels
which have the same color as pixel (0, 0) will be made
transparent&per. 
.br
:li.
You should be very careful in replacing these bitmaps&per.
The transparency calculations are extremely CPU-intensive&per.
If you use a 500x500 pixel bitmap with half of the pixels
transparent, this can block your system for many minutes&per.
And I mean :hp1.block,:ehp1. because most of the calculating time
is consumed by Presentation Manager (PM), and this will
usually hang the whole system&per. 
:p.
If everything goes wrong and your WPS won't start any
more, you can :hp2.hold down the "Shift" key:ehp2. while the WPS
is starting up&per. This will display the :link reftype=hd res=10064."Startup panic"
dialog:elink., where you can disable the boot logo and take
care of the problem after the WPS is up&per. 
:p.
Since PM was designed to display rectangular windows
only, the way these "shape" windows are done is that
the bitmap is analyzed pixel by pixel and as many PM
subwindows are created as rectangular non-transparent
areas exist in the bitmap&per. 
:p.
For this reason, be very careful with transparency&per.
The more non-rectangular transparent areas are in the
bitmap, the more windows have to be created&per. 
:p.
Example&colon. 
:cgraphic.         ⁄ƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒø
         ≥                    ≥
         ≥   11111111111111   ≥
         ≥   11111111111111   ≥
         ≥   2222      3333   ≥
         ≥   44444444444444   ≥
         ≥   44444444444444   ≥
         ≥                    ≥
         ¿ƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒŸ
:ecgraphic.
:p.
(where " " is a transparent pixel) would result in the
creation of exactly four subwindows (marked as "1"-"4")&per.

:p.
However, if you have "diagonal" or other non-rectangular
transparency in your bitmap, one or several subwindows
have to be created :hp1.for each line:ehp1. of the bitmap, which
can really make PM busy&per. 
:p.
Another example&colon. 
:cgraphic.         ⁄ƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒø
         ≥                    ≥
         ≥   111111111        ≥
         ≥    2222  333       ≥
         ≥     44     55      ≥
         ≥      666 777777    ≥
         ≥       8888888888   ≥
         ≥        9999999999  ≥
         ≥                    ≥
         ¿ƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒŸ
:ecgraphic.
:p.
This would already create nine windows&colon. one for
the top line, then two each for the following lines,
and another one for each of the bottom lines&per. So
imagine such an image with 500 lines&colon. this would
create at least 500 subwindows&per. 
:p.
To make this clear&colon. it's not the parsing of the
bitmap which uses a lot of CPU time&per. It's the creation
of subwindows&per. So large bitmaps will not hurt if
there's very little or only rectangular transparency&per.

:p.
I found this out the hard way when I accidently dithered
a bitmap to the system color palette&per. Suddenly,
there were hundreds of transparent and non-transparent
areas alternating (because the background which I intended
was dithered)&per. 
:p.
The bitmap had about 100 lines, and I got several 1000
windows&per. I pressed Ctrl-Alt-Del after about two
minutes&per. 
:p.
So be warned&per. Start out with small bitmaps and see
what your system can handle&per. For large bitmaps,
try to make the transparent areas rectangular&per. Do
not dither bitmaps, but use plain colors instead&per.

:eol.
:p.

.br

.* Source file: "xsd_1restartwps.html"
:h2 res=10067 x=right width=70%.Restart Desktop
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XFldObject, XFldDesktop:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
XWorkplace can also add a "Restart Desktop" item to
the context menu of the Desktop&per. 
:p.
After selecting "Restart Desktop", a dialog box similar
to the one of the :link reftype=hd res=10068.Extended Shutdown:elink. will appear&per.
The difference is that after all windows have been closed,
not the whole computer is restarted, but only the Workplace
Shell Process (PMSHELL&per.EXE)&per. 
:p.
To understand the difference it might be helpful to
know that the OS/2 user interface is structured into
three "layers", so-to-say, which sit on top of each
other&colon. 
:cgraphic.
   ⁄ƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒø
   ≥  Workplace Shell (WPS)      ≥
   ¿ƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒŸ
   ⁄ƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒø
   ≥  Presentation Manager (PM)  ≥
   ¿ƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒŸ
   ⁄ƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒø
   ≥  OS/2 Kernel                ≥
   ¿ƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒƒŸ

:ecgraphic.
:p.

.br
The :hp2.OS/2 Kernel:ehp2. provides the basic functionality of
the operating system, such as device access and multitasking&per.
Without it, nothing would work on your system&per. 
:p.
The :hp2.Presentation Manager (PM):ehp2. is responsible for the
graphics on your system, such as windows, icons, menus,
pictures, and a few more non-graphical things, such
as INI files&per. OS/2 can run text-mode applications
(e&per.g&per. the OS/2 command line, CMD&per.EXE) without
PM, but all other applications require that PM be running&per.
A typical PM application is Netscape, for example&per.

:p.
The :hp2.Workplace Shell (WPS):ehp2. is just another, however very
complex PM application&per. It is responsible for displaying
folders, starting programs when you double-click on
their icons, associating files to programs, in short&colon.
everything you see after your OS/2 has finished booting&per.
This is the context in which XWorkplace is running&per.

:p.
The :hp2."Restart Desktop":ehp2. menu item now terminates the topmost
layer of the aforementioned three only, the Workplace
Shell&per. This takes a lot less time than rebooting
your whole computer, because PM and the Kernel need
not be reloaded and initialized&per. 
:p.
Restarting the WPS can be helpful when your system has
become really slow (for some reason, at least judging
from my personal experience, the WPS eats up more and
more memory when you work with files a lot) or if you
have installed software which changes WPS classes&per.
:hp2.
:p.
Important notes&colon.:ehp2. 
:ul compact.:li.
Please keep in mind that this is not the way of restarting
the Workplace Shell that IBM intended when developing
it&per. "Restart Desktop" forces the WPS to restart
by simply terminating it&per. Since XWorkplace is part
of the WPS process, it can simply exit&per. OS/2 will
then restart this process automatically&per. The result
is almost the same as if the WPS had crashed and was
restarted, although the WPS data will be saved before
restarting&per. 
.br
:li.
On my system, the icons of executables in folders get
scrambled after a Desktop restart&per. This applies
to all program objects and executable files which are
not assigned an individual icon to (via their Settings
notebooks)&per. Either icons get completely lost or
wrong icons are displayed&per. This is a bug in the
Presentation Manager, on which I have no influence&per.
After a complete reboot, the correct icons are restored&per.

.br
:li.
Neither Presentation Manager nor :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.CONFIG&per.SYS:font facename=default size=0x0. settings
are re-read upon restarting the WPS&per. If these settings
have changed, a Desktop restart will not recognize these
changes&per. Reboot instead&per. 
.br
:li.
As a general rule, the more WPS classes you have installed,
the more problems are likely to arise when restarting
the WPS&per. This can be due to many reasons, which
I don't fully understand, but for one certain third-party
WPS classes do not seem to clean up allocated resources
properly when the WPS is terminated&per. Second, the
SOM kernel does seem to get confused sometimes with
WPS class replacements, and some parts of the WPS then
crash about 20 seconds after the Desktop has been populated&per.

:p.
In these cases, you will be reported fairly random crashes
in certain DLLs, which are just symptoms of something
going wrong internally&per. If this happens, you will
have to reboot&per. Candidates for these random DLL
crashes that I have unveiled are INSTALL&per.DLL (contains
WPInstall), WPPRINT&per.DLL (contains the printer and
spooler classes), and also the WorkFrame which comes
with the various IBM compilers&per. (Amusingly, all
those DLLs have been programmed by IBM&per.) 
.br
:li.
Depending on your system, the number of Desktop restarts
you may successfully execute will be limited&per. Some
users have reported that this works only once, on my
system I've successfully restarted the WPS many times
(about 30) before the system crashed&per. (This sounds
like many times, but when programming XWorkplace, this
is necessary, unfortunately&per.) 
:eul.
:p.
You can turn this feature off on a new settings page
of the Desktop's Settings notebook&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "xsd_2xshutdown.html"
:h2 res=10068 x=right width=70%.Extended Shutdown
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XFldObject, XFldDesktop:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
One of the major features of XWorkplace is to improve
the shutdown procedure of OS/2&per. :hp2.
:p.
Important note&colon.:ehp2. XShutdown is disabled per default
in order to avoid confusion&per. You will need to enable
XShutdown in the new :link reftype=hd res=10083."XWorkplace Setup" object:elink.&per.

:p.
After enabling XShutdown, selecting "Shutdown" from
the Desktop's context menu will start XWorkplace's shutdown
procedure instead of OS/2's standard shutdown&per. 
:p.
After selecting "Shutdown", a dialog box similar to
the following will pop up&colon. 
:artwork name='shutdown2.bmp' align=left.
:p.
The main new features of XShutdown are&colon. 
:ul compact.:li.
You can choose to :hp2.automatically reboot:ehp2. your computer
after shutdown has completed&per. 
:p.
You may even create your own reboot options, e&per.g&per.
reboot to a certain Boot Manager partition directly&per.
This is explained in detail when you press the "Actions"
button on page 1 of the "XDesktop" pages in the Desktop's
settings notebook&per. 
.br
:li.
XShutdown can be :hp2.cancelled:ehp2. even after shutdown has started&per.

.br
:li.
XShutdown will display the progress of the shutdown
procedure, and if some application "hangs", i&per.e&per.
it cannot be closed, you can choose to :hp2.skip:ehp2. it and continue
the shutdown sequence without waiting for this application
to close&colon. 
:artwork name='shutdown.bmp' align=left.
:eul.
:p.
The automatic reboot requires that DOS&per.SYS be installed
through :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.CONFIG&per.SYS:font facename=default size=0x0.&per. On Warp 4, this is done
per default&per. On OS/2 Warp 3, you might need to add
the following line to :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.CONFIG&per.SYS:font facename=default size=0x0.&colon. :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.
:p.
DEVICE=X&colon.\OS2\BOOT\DOS&per.SYS:font facename=default size=0x0. 
:p.
with X&colon. being your OS/2 boot drive&per. 
:p.
You can configure (and turn off) the eXtended Shutdown
on a new settings page of the :link reftype=hd res=10055.Desktop's Settings:elink. notebook&per.

:p.
If you're interested in how XShutdown works internally,
please see the :link reftype=hd res=10128.respective page:elink. in the "XWorkplace Internals"
chapter&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "xsd_3folders.html"
:h2 res=10069 x=right width=70%.Startup and Shutdown Folders
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XFldObject, XFldDesktop, XFolder, XFldStartup,
XFldShutdown:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
XWorkplace offers you separate startup and shutdown
folders&per. :hp2.
:p.
Note&colon.:ehp2. The startup and shutdown folders are not
automatically created by the install program to avoid
confusion&per. Please open the :link reftype=hd res=10082."XWorkplace Setup":elink. object
to create them manually&per. 
:p.
If XWorkplace finds the :hp2.XWorkplace Startup Folder:ehp2. upon
Desktop startup, it will process its contents in a way
much similar to what the WPS does with its own startup
folder&per. The main differences are&colon. 
:ul compact.:li.
You may set a certain time which XWorkplace will wait
in between starting objects&per. The conventional startup
folder sometimes leads to problems if you have many
objects in there, which are normally all started at
the same time, sometimes causing the WPS to hang at
startup&per. This delay can be changed in the XWorkplace
Startup folder's own settings notebook&per. 
.br
:li.
You will be able to watch the progress of the startup
process in a separate window (which can also be turned
off in the XWorkplace Startup folder's own settings
notebook, if you don't like it)&per. 
.br
:li.
Startup can be cancelled while it is running&per. 
.br
:li.
Startup can completely be skipped by holding down the
"Shift" key during WPS startup, which makes the :link reftype=hd res=10064."Startup
panic" dialog:elink. appear&per. 
.br
:li.
The XWorkplace Startup Folder is also processed after
a Desktop restart, while the regular Desktop startup
folder is not&per. This applies only if you had selected
the respective checkbox in the "Restart Desktop" confirmation
dialog box&per. 
.br
:li.
The XWorkplace Startup Folder now (V0&per.80) has a
"Start folder content" menu item which allows you to
have its contents started even after the WPS is up&per.

:eul.
:p.
On the other hand, the :hp2.XWorkplace Shutdown Folder:ehp2. will
be processed before the eXtended Shutdown (and not before
the regular shutdown)&per. As opposed to with the Startup
Folder, you may not set a delay here, but XWorkplace
waits before starting the next object until the currently
opened object has been closed again&per. Only if all
objects started from the Shutdown Folder have been closed,
the eXtended Shutdown actually begins&per. 
:p.
The Shutdown folder can be useful if you need to have
certain programs executed before turning off your system&per.
You could, for example, create some REXX script which
does some cleanup before shutting down, such as properly
logging off your network, deleting TEMP files, or whatever
you can think of&per. 
:p.
For both the XWorkplace Startup and Shutdown folders,
you may define the order in which objects are started&per.
This works just the same way as described on the :link reftype=hd res=10043.respective
page:elink. for the XWorkplace Configuration Folders&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "xsd_4cmdline.html"
:h2 res=10070 x=right width=70%.Shutting Down from the Command Line
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XFldObject, XFldDesktop:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
It is possible to start the extended shutdown procedure
from the command line as well&per. From version 0&per.80
to 0&per.9&per.6, XFolder/XWorkplace used to contain
an external executable for this task&per. This has been
removed with V0&per.9&per.7 because it caused too much
confusion since all those command line parameters were
not easy to use&per. 
:p.
Instead, with V0&per.9&per.7, XWorkplace supports external
shutdown with the use of new WPS setup strings for the
desktop&per. In summary, you can invoke the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XSHUTDOWNNOW=DEFAULT:font facename=default size=0x0.
setup string on your desktop, and your system will be
shut down as if you had selected the "Shutdown" menu
item from the desktop's context menu&per. 
:p.
For a detailed description of the setup strings available,
see the setup strings for XFldDesktop in the :link reftype=hd res=10021.appendices:elink.
of this book&per. 
.br

