.* Source file: "mouse_1intro.html"
:h2 res=10071 x=right width=70%.Introduction
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XFldObject, XWPSetup, XWPMouse, XWPKeyboard:ehp2.
:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
Starting with V0&per.9&per.0, XWorkplace also introduces
a number of mouse and keyboard enhancements by installing
a Presentation Manager hook, similar to what well-known
enhancers such as FeelX, NPS WPS, and WarpEnhancer do&per.

:p.
So XWorkplace now also goes for features like "sliding
focus", "hot corners", and "object hotkeys"&per. These
are described in detail on the following pages&per.

:p.
The ultimate goal for this XWorkplace component is to
replace all those PM hook utilities one day&per. In
my view, several problems exist with those utilities&colon.

:ol compact.:li.
Most importantly, most of these have not been actively
maintained for years&per. This especially applies to
FeelX and NPS WPS, both of which I have been using for
years&per. However, both of them have a few limitations
which will never be overcome because they probably won't
ever be updated again&per. 
.br
:li.
Both utilities are not well integrated into the WPS&per.
That is, their settings cannot be changed using the
standard WPS notebooks&per. XWorkplace allows you to
configure its PM hook using the "Mouse" and "Keyboard"
objects in the "System Setup" folder&per. And NPS WPS
always terminates itself when the WPS is restarted,
which is pretty annoying&per. 
.br
:li.
None of the well-known PM hook utilities are OpenSource,
except ProgramCommander/2 (which is even public domain)&per.
XWorkplace is OpenSource, so bugs can be reported and/or
fixed by users&per. 
.br
:li.
Finally, I just hate to install three different PM hooks
when I only need a single feature from each of these&per.
Each installed PM hook slows down the system, because
every single message which is produced by OS/2 and posted
or sent to a window must go thru all of these hooks,
each of which does a lot of calculations for that message&per.
And we're talking about possibly hundreds of messages
per second here&per. So instead of having three hooks
installed which are only partly used, XWorkplace attempts
to put the most frequently-used features all together
in one hook&per. 
:eol.
:p.
Note that the XWorkplace PM hook is a completely optional
feature&per. If you don't like it and prefer to still
use other utilites, feel free to do so&per. 
:p.
For this reason, the XWorkplace hook is disabled per
default&per. It must be enabled first in the "XWorkplace
Setup" object&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "mouse_2sliding.html"
:h2 res=10072 x=right width=70%.Sliding Focus
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XWPSetup, XWPMouse:ehp2. :cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
XWorkplace's "sliding focus" feature is very similar
to that offered by many other PM hooks&per. 
:p.
Basically, this feature means that the keyboard input
focus always follows the mouse pointer&per. That is,
if you move the mouse, the window under the mouse pointer
will be given the input focus (which means that also
the title bar will be made active)&per. 
:p.
This behavior is very common with the various window
managers running on the X-Window windowing system used
with the many flavors of UNIX, and Linux has inherited
this also&per. Since many people prefer to have this
behavior with OS/2 too (including myself), this has
been included with XWorkplace&per. 
:p.
This feature can be :hp2.configured:ehp2. in the "Mouse" object,
which usually resides in your "System Setup" folder&per.
On the "Movement" page in that object, there are several
settings&per. Press the "Help" button on that page to
find out more&per. :hp2.
:p.
Note&colon.:ehp2. That page is only visible if the XWPMouse
class is installed and the XWorkplace hook has been
enabled in :link reftype=hd res=10082."XWorkplace Setup"&per.:elink. 
:p.
The main advantage of this feature is that for one,
you don't have to click into a window to be able to
use the keyboard with it&per. Also, if you have disabled
the "Bring window to top" setting on the "Mouse hook"
page, you can even type into a window which is not the
topmost window, which is impossible without the "Sliding
focus" feature&per. This takes a bit of getting used
to, but this can be very handy when several windows
are opened and you need to view one window's information
while typing into another&per. :hp2.
:p.
Notes:ehp2. 
:ol compact.:li.
There's no way to make this feature work properly with
:hp2.seamless Win-OS/2 windows&per.:ehp2. The 16-bit Windows graphics
engine (Graphical Device Interface, GDI) is not capable
of differentiating between a "topmost" and an "active"
window; it simply assumes that the topmost window must
always be the active one&per. This limitation applies
to seamless Win-OS/2 windows also, which use the 16-bit
Windows graphics engine internally&per. 
:p.
For this reason, there is a special setting on the "Movement"
page in the "Mouse" settings notebook for Win-OS/2 windows&per.
You can either decide to always bring Win-OS/2 windows
to the top, or to ignore them completely&per. It is
however not possible to make them active without bringing
them to the top&per. Otherwise you'd get really strange
repainting errors on your screen, because the GDI would
repaint an active Win-OS/2 window completely even if
other windows are on top of it (because it assumes it
must be the topmost window)&per. 
:p.
Of course, full-screen Win-OS/2 sessions are not affected
by XWorkplace in any way, because the XWorkplace PM
hook does not deal with Win-OS/2 fullscreen sessions&per.

.br
:li.
While the :hp2.PM window list:ehp2. (or tasklist) is showing on
the screen, the sliding focus feature is temporarily
disabled&per. This is necessary because the window list
automatically disappears when it loses the keyboard
focus&per. If the sliding focus weren't disabled while
the window list is showing, it would become difficult
to do anything with the window list at all, because
it would kept disappearing if the mouse pointer was
not over it&per. 
:eol.
:p.

