:p.
While :link reftype=hd res=10072."Sliding focus":elink. affects desktop windows, XWorkplace's
"sliding menus" feature affects open menus&per. This
applies to pull-down menus as well as popup (context)
menus&per. 
:p.
This feature can be enabled on the "Movement" page in
the "Mouse" settings object as well, if the XWPMouse
class is installed and the XWorkplace hook has been
enabled in :link reftype=hd res=10082."XWorkplace Setup"&per.:elink. 
:p.
If this is enabled, the menu selection in an open menu
will follow the mouse pointer&per. 
:p.
This feature can be configured in several ways&per.
You can choose to have a behavior as with NPSWPS, that
is, the menu behaves as if you held down mouse button
1 all the time&per. 
:p.
However, you can also choose to make menus behave as
with Windows 95, if you prefer&per. To do this, on the
"Movement" page in the "Mouse" settings object, raise
the "Submenu delay" and enable the "Immediate hilite"
setting as well&per. 
:p.
Detailed help is available if you press the "Help" button
on the "Movement" page&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "mouse_4mb3.html"
:h2 res=10074 x=right width=70%.Mouse Button 3 Features
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XWPSetup, XWPMouse:ehp2. :cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
If you have a three-button mouse, XWorkplace's PM hook
also allows you to reconfigure mouse button 3 (the middle
mouse button on most mice) to do useful things, since
that button is normally useless with OS/2 and most OS/2
applications&per. 
:p.
There are two mouse button 3 features at this point&colon.

:ul compact.:li.
XWorkplace allows to have all single mouse button 3
clicks converted to :hp2.mouse button 1 double clicks&per.:ehp2.
This allows you, for example, to click on a Desktop
object with mouse button 3 once, and the object will
be opened as if you had double-clicked on it&per. 
.br
:li.
XWorkplace also allows you to :hp2.scroll windows contents:ehp2.
by dragging the mouse while mouse button 3 is held down&per.
If the window under the mouse has scroll bars, the window
will be scrolled as if you had used the scroll bars
even if the mouse is somewhere else over the window's
contents&per. This saves you a lot of mouse mileage&per.

:eul.
:p.
Both features can be enabled in the "Mouse" object on
the new second "Mappings" page, which is added by XWorkplace&per.
There are a lot of configuration options to adjust these
features to your needs&per. Press the "Help" button
on that page for details&per. :hp2.
:p.
Note&colon.:ehp2. That page is only visible if the XWPMouse
class is installed :hp1.and:ehp1. the XWorkplace hook has been
enabled in :link reftype=hd res=10082."XWorkplace Setup"&per.:elink. 
.br

.* Source file: "mouse_81objhotkeys.html"
:h2 res=10075 x=right width=70%.Object Hotkeys
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XFldObject, XWPSetup, XWPKeyboard:ehp2. :cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
Starting with V0&per.9&per.0, XWorkplace also introduces
"object hotkeys", which means that you can open any
object in its default view by pressing a certain hotkey
combination, which you can define individually for each
object&per. 
:p.
As with all XWorkplace hook features, object hotkeys
are disabled per default&per. You need to enable them
in the "XWorkplace setup" object first&per. :hp2.
:p.
Note&colon.:ehp2. Do not confuse object hotkeys with :link reftype=hd res=10053.folder
hotkeys,:elink. as displayed in the "Workplace Shell" settings
object&per. Object hotkeys are used to open objects
using a key definition and work everywhere, while folder
hotkeys are shortcuts to certain folder commands and
work in folders only&per. 
:p.
Object hotkeys can be :hp2.configured:ehp2. in two places&per.
For one, XWorkplace inserts a new "Object" page into
each single :hp2.object's settings notebook&per.:ehp2. This applies
to really all objects (that is, folders, files, printers,
program objects, etc&per.)&per. By clicking into the
"Hotkey" entry field, you may define a key combination
for that object&per. From then on, if you press this
key combination anywhere on your system, the object
will be opened in its default view (as if you had double-clicked
on it)&per. 
:p.
Secondly, XWorkplace inserts a new page into the :hp2."Keyboard"
settings object,:ehp2. which per default resides in your "System
Setup" folder&per. On this new page, which is called
"Hotkeys" for some reason, all currently defined object
hotkeys are listed&per. 
:p.
There are some :hp2.limitations:ehp2. with respect to object hotkeys&per.
Since hotkey detection is done in the XWorkplace PM
hook, object hotkeys only work in the Presentation Manager
(PM) screen session&per. This includes all PM applications,
the WPS itself, plus windowed (seamless) OS/2, DOS and
Win-OS/2 sessions, but :hp1.not:ehp1. DOS, OS/2 or Win-OS/2 :hp1.fullscreen:ehp1.
sessions, unfortunately&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "mouse_82funckeys.html"
:h2 res=10076 x=right width=70%.Registering Extra Function Keys
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XWPKeyboard:ehp2. :cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
Starting with V0&per.9&per.3, XWorkplace allows you
to give certain keys which normally don't work under
OS/2 a special meaning&per. You can then use those extra
keys as object hotkeys as well&per. In order for this
to work, you will need to register those keys with the
"Function keys" page in the enhanced "Keyboard" object&per.

:p.
This feature is implemented through the XWorkplace PM
hook as well&per. To understand how this is working
(and before you use the "Function keys" page), the following
explanations should be understood&per. 
:p.
Keyboard processing is a complex issue under any operating
system&per. It involves interpreting hardware messages
and translating those according to the current language
settings&per. 
:p.
Under OS/2, this processing is done on several layers
of the system&per. For one, there is the hardware keyboard
device driver which gets loaded though a BASEDEV statement
in :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.CONFIG&per.SYS:font facename=default size=0x0.&per. This one reacts to hardware interrupts
raised by the physical keyboard hardware and thus receives
really every single keystroke on the system&per. 
:p.
The OS/2 Kernel then processes those keystrokes for
the application which currently has the input focus&per.
Further processing is different depending on the type
of application&per. Presentation Manager (PM) applications
(including the Workplace Shell) usually receive a message
that a key has been pressed or released&per. The XWorkplace
PM hook can thus intercept these messages and manipulate
them&per. (This is how :link reftype=hd res=10075.object hotkeys:elink. work as well,
by the way&per.) 
:p.
Unfortunately, the default OS/2 keyboard processing
is still based on the original 101/102-key IBM-compatible
AT keyboards introduced in the 1980's&per. Today, many
keyboards have additional keys which are not recognized
at all by OS/2 or simply produce a character output
even though they aren't really supposed to&per. 
:p.
Those extra function keys could be the three "Windows"
keys found on most keyboards sold today&per. In addition,
there are some extended keyboards which have additional
"multimedia" keys&per. Also, many laptops have some
extra keys&per. 
:p.
The XWorkplace PM hook can identify the physical key
which has actually been pressed by evaluating the :hp2.hardware
scan code:ehp2. of the key, which is passed to any PM application
directly from the keyboard hardware&per. On every keyboard,
every key should have a unique such code&per. This code
has nothing to do with the ASCII code of a character,
it's just a unique number assigned to each physical
key on the keyboard&per. For example, the "Shift" key
will have such a code as well as the "A" key, even though
the "Shift" key alone will produce no ASCII (character)
output&per. 
:p.
So the XWorkplace hook needs to know the hardware scan
code of your function keys in order to be able to react
to them&per. As a result, you will need to :hp2.register:ehp2.
your extra keys with XWorkplace&per. Those keys are
then called :hp2."XWorkplace function keys":ehp2. and will be recognized
by XWorkplace&per. You can, for example, use them as
:link reftype=hd res=10075.object hotkeys:elink. after having registered them&per. 
:p.
To :hp2.register such a function key with XWorkplace,:ehp2. go
to the enhanced "Keyboard" object and switch to the
new "Function keys" page&per. Right-click on the container
whitespace and select "Add function key"&per. You'll
get additional help by pressing the "Help" buttons there&per.
:hp2.
:p.
Warnings&per.:ehp2. 
:ol compact.:li.
There is virtually :hp2.no error checking:ehp2. when registering
a function key with XWorkplace&per. Scan codes are hardware-dependent,
so there's no way for XWorkplace to tell whether a certain
scan code really shouldn't be registered&per. For example,
you could also register the "Enter" or any character
key as a function key, which really isn't a good idea&per.
:hp2.So register only "real" extra keys with XWorkplace,
or the key might no longer work&per.:ehp2. 
.br
:li.
Some keys will refuse to be registered&per. If this
happens, this means that the keyboard hardware doesn't
produce a scan code for the key&per. I have a Fujitsu
multimedia keyboard with some 15 extra keys, and three
of them just don't work&per. I guess we'd need a device
driver to interpret those extra three keys, but this
is beyond my knowledge&per. 
.br
:li.
As usual, the function keys will only be detected while
a PM window has the focus&per. They will not work in
full-screen DOS or full-screen Win-OS/2 sessions&per.

:eol.
:p.

