.* Source file: "pgmg_1intro.html"
:h2 res=10077 x=right width=70%.Introduction
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XWPScreen:ehp2. :cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
XPager was originally PageMage, a freeware program written
by Carlos Ugarte&per. From what I know, the last public
version was 0&per.36&per. Since the author no longer
had the time to work on it, he published the sources
under the GPL&per. 
:p.
While earlier XWorkplace versions were still based on
the original PageMage sources, this is no longer the
case&per. XPager is a complete rewrite, even though
it may look quite similar and borrowed some good ideas
from PageMage&per. 
:p.
XPager is initially disabled&per. To turn it on, go
to the "Features" page in the :link reftype=hd res=10083."XWorkplace Setup" object:elink.
and check the respective box&per. This requires that
the :hp2.XWorkplace PM hook:ehp2. also be installed&per. 
:p.
XPager is a :hp2.virtual desktop utility for OS/2&per.:ehp2. Essentially,
it allows the user to work on several desktops at once&per.
Your screen is considered one out of several, and you
can switch between these&per. This effectively multiplies
your working area since windows can reside outside your
currently visible desktop and still be switched to simply
by switching to another desktop&per. 
:artwork name='pagemage.bmp' align=left.
:p.
Traditionally, most virtual desktop programs show a
representation of the overall desktop in a window, highlighting
the current desktop&per. The standard mechanism for
switching desktops has been to click (with a mouse)
on one of the other desktops, which would remove the
current desktop's windows and display the new desktop's
windows&per. 
:p.
XPager can be :hp2.configured:ehp2. in the new :link reftype=hd res=10082."Screen" settings
object,:elink. where XWorkplace inserts several pages&per.

.br

.* Source file: "pgmg_2moving.html"
:h2 res=10078 x=right width=70%.Moving Around
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XWPScreen:ehp2. :cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
There are several ways to move between desktops in XPager&colon.

:ul compact.:li.
Click on the appropriate desktop in the :hp2.XPager window:ehp2.
with the left mouse button&per. 
.br
:li.
You can use :hp2.special global hotkeys:ehp2. for switching between
desktops&per. Those are the cursor arrow keys plus any
combination of the Ctrl, Alt and Shift modifiers&per.

:p.
You can change the modifiers in the new :link reftype=hd res=10082."Screen" settings
object,:elink. but the arrow keys are hard-coded into XPager
and cannot be changed&per. 
:p.
Those hotkeys work even if you have XWorkplace's :link reftype=hd res=10075.global
object hotkeys:elink. disabled&per. However, these hotkeys
must be turned on first, which can be done in the "Screen"
settings object as well&per. 
:eul.
:p.

.* Source file: "pgmg_3sticky.html"
:h2 res=10079 x=right width=70%.Sticky Windows
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XWPScreen:ehp2. :cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
A :hp2.sticky window:ehp2. is a window that is always visible on
all desktops&per. While this may seem to be "wasting
space", sticky windows can be very useful&per. 
:p.
There are some applications which are small in screen
space consumption, such as clocks, resource monitors,
program launchers, which you might prefer to see on
all desktops&per. You can therefore declare them as
sticky on the XPager settings pages in the :link reftype=hd res=10082."Screen"
settings object&per.:elink. 
:p.
XPager identifies a window as sticky according to its
switch list title&per. For details, refer to the help
page on the settings page in the :link reftype=hd res=10082."Screen" settings object&per.:elink.

:p.
There are two windows that are always sticky&colon.
the XPager window itself, and the Workplace Shell Desktop&per.
Besides, minimized windows are always sticky if you
have configured minimized windows to appear on the Desktop&per.

.br

.* Source file: "pgmg_8howwork.html"
:h2 res=10080 x=right width=70%.How It Works
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XWPScreen:ehp2. :cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
XPager needs :hp2.no special hardware:ehp2. to implement these
virtual desktops&per. While the various implementations
of the Unix X Window system (one of which is XFree/2,
which runs under OS/2) can actually use additional memory
on your video card to have room for several desktops,
XPager simply moves windows around your screen&per.

:p.
To make this clear&colon. With XPager, technically,
you still only have one screen&per. Neither PM nor your
video driver know anything about virtual desktops&per.
All XPager does when switching desktops is to move windows
off of and onto your one visible screen&per. That is,
if you switch one desktop to the right, XPager moves
all windows to the left by the size of your physical
screen (which makes them invisible, of course)&per.
As a result, no special hardware or software or drivers
are required&per. If your computer can handle moving
windows, it can use XPager&per. 
:p.
The small XPager pager window then does a number of
calculations to make all windows look as if they were
part of a huge virtual screen, but your physical screen
really doesn't change -- it's the windows that are moved&per.

:p.
XPager also needs the XWorkplace PM hook to be able
to track window movement -- for one, to reflect window
changes in the XPager window, secondly to be informed
when windows are created or destroyed for any reason&per.
It can then, for example, automatically switch desktops
(that is, move all windows) if the focus is given to
a window of another desktop&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "mouse_3hotcorners.html"
:h2 res=10081 x=right width=70%.Screen Border Objects
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XWPSetup, XWPScreen:ehp2. :cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
XWorkplace also implements "screen border objects",
which means that you can configure the XWorkplace PM
hook to automatically open a certain object in its default
view if the mouse pointer is moved to one of the four
corners or one of the four borders of your screen&per.
You can also configure the XWorkplace PM hook to initiate
desktop switching in such cases if XPager is enabled&per.

:p.
For example, on my system, I have configured this feature
to automatically open the "Drives" folder when I move
the mouse pointer to the top-right corner of the screen&per.

:p.
In addition to opening objects, XWorkplace can also
display the PM window list with this feature&per. :hp2.
:p.
Note&colon.:ehp2. That page is only visible if the XWPScreen
class is installed :hp1.and:ehp1. the XWorkplace hook has been
enabled in :link reftype=hd res=10082."XWorkplace Setup"&per.:elink. 
.br

