.* Source file: "sys_1intro.html"
:h2 res=10082 x=right width=70%.Introduction
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XWPSetup, XFldWPS, XFldSystem, XWPClassList:ehp2.
:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
After XWorkplace has been installed, you will find a
number of new settings objects in your "System setup"
folder&per. Also, most of the new XWorkplace objects
have some new settings pages too&per. This might seem
a bit overwhelming at first, but I did try to follow
a certain logic when implementing all the settings&per.

:ul compact.
.br
:li.

:artwork name='xwsetup.bmp' runin align=left.Starting with V0&per.9&per.0, XWorkplace introduces
a new global settings object called :hp2."XWorkplace Setup":ehp2.&per.
This has a number of settings pages to monitor the status
of some XWorkplace internals, globally enable or disable
the major XWorkplace features that you might or might
not be interested in, and some more troubleshooting
settings&per. 
:p.
Those items are explained in detail when you press the
"Help" button on those new settings pages&per. 
.br
:li.

:artwork name='xfwps.bmp' runin align=left.The new :hp2."Workplace Shell":ehp2. object contains those pages
from the old "System" object which deal with the Workplace
Shell only&per. I felt these are not really "System"
settings and deserve a separate object&per. 
:p.
XWorkplace also adds most of its own settings pages
here, because these mostly affect the Workplace Shell&per.
This is described in more detail on the :link reftype=hd res=10083."Global Settings":elink.
page in this reference&per. 
.br
:li.

:artwork name='xclslist.bmp' runin align=left.There is another new object which contains the :hp2."WPS
Class List":ehp2.&per. This used to be on a settings page
in the "Workplace Shell" object before XWorkplace V0&per.9&per.0,
but that page proved to be a bit small to get all the
information in there&per. 
.br
:li.

:artwork name='xfsys.bmp' runin align=left.The new :hp2."OS/2 Kernel":ehp2. object contains those pages from
the old "System" object which deal with OS/2's internals,
e&per.g&per. the "Screen" settings&per. 
:p.
In this object you'll find several new settings pages
to change a number of settings in the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.CONFIG&per.SYS:font facename=default size=0x0.
file in the root directory of your boot drive&per. Since
these settings are a bit hard to remember and since
erroneous settings in this file might even lead to OS/2
not booting any more, XWorkplace tries to help you by
setting this up automatically&per. 
:p.
On each of these new settings pages, which will be explained
in more detail on the following pages, you will find
a button called "Update :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.CONFIG&per.SYS:font facename=default size=0x0." instead of the
usual "Undo" and "Default" buttons&per. Pressing this
button will cause the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.CONFIG&per.SYS:font facename=default size=0x0. file to be rewritten
according to the settings you've changed&per. 
:p.
The different settings are explained in great detail
if you press the :hp2."Help":ehp2. button on one of the settings
pages&per. 
.br
:li.

:artwork name='xwpscreen.bmp' runin align=left.The :hp2."Screen":ehp2. settings object is new with V0&per.9&per.3
and holds those settings pages from the old "System"
object which deal with the screen&per. In addition,
if you have :link reftype=hd res=10010.XPager:elink. enabled, several settings pages are
inserted here as well to configure XPager&per. 
:eul.
:p.
The :hp2.old "System" object:ehp2. continues to work, in case other
WPS enhancers try to insert anything into this object&per.
Such extensions will also appear in the new "OS/2 Kernel"
object, which inherits the "System" characteristics&per.

:p.
Please note that you should not open the old "System"
object and one of the new objects together to change
settings&per. The settings pages are not prepared for
this, and this might mess up the WPS settings&per. 
:p.
Additional settings pages can be found in the settings
notebooks of each folder, the Desktop, the :link reftype=hd res=10069.XWorkplace
startup folder:elink., and the :link reftype=hd res=10061.XWorkplace trash can:elink.&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "sys_2global.html"
:h2 res=10083 x=right width=70%.XWorkplace Global Settings
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XWPSetup, XFldWPS:ehp2. :cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
With the XWorkplace Global Settings, you can make XWorkplace
behave differently&per. Here you will find settings
which affect XWorkplace in general, such as its language
support, as well as settings which will affect your
computer as a whole&per. This is why they're called
"global settings", as opposed to individual folder settings,
which are explained on a :link reftype=hd res=10055.separate page:elink.&per. 
:p.
The major features of XWorkplace can be enabled or disabled
in the new :hp2."XWorkplace Setup":ehp2. object&per. Depending
on the settings on the "Features" page, certain parts
of XWorkplace will be completely disabled&per. This
might be useful if you are only interested in certain
features or if you have problems with others&per. 
.br

:artwork name='xwsetup.bmp' runin align=left.New "XWorkplace Setup" object 
:p.
The detailed settings for the various XWorkplace features
however are in the :hp2."Workplace Shell":ehp2. object, which you
will also find in your "System setup" folder&per. 
.br

:artwork name='xfwps.bmp' runin align=left.New "Workplace Shell" object 
:p.
Note that if you disable features in "XWorkplace Setup",
some settings pages in "Workplace Shell" will not be
shown if they don't make sense without a feature being
enabled&per. 
:p.
The different settings pages are not explained in detail
here&per. You will find extensive help by pressing F1
or the "Help" button, which exists on every page&per.

.br

