.* Source file: "nsd_4tips.html"
:h2 res=10087 x=right width=70%.Tips &amp. Tricks
:p.

:ol compact.:li.
Here's an unintended, but maybe useful side-effect&colon.
Since OS/2 can share its DDE environment with a Win-OS/2
session, NETSCDDE can even pass URLs to a running :hp2.Win-OS/2
copy:ehp2. of Netscape Navigator&per. This includes Communicator
(Netscape 4)&per. The only thing you have to do is enable
WIN_DDE in the Win-OS/2 session settings of your Windows
Netscape program object&per. By specifying your Windows
Netscape EXE file with :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.-p <exe>:font facename=default size=0x0. (see above), NETSCDDE&per.EXE
even provides for proper WPS integration of Windows
Netscapes&per. 
.br
:li.
You can now (V1&per.1) also specify a :hp2.&per.CMD file:ehp2.
with :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.-p:font facename=default size=0x0. and :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.-P:font facename=default size=0x0. to have certain commands executed before
and after Netscape is actually started&per. You should
specify the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.-m:font facename=default size=0x0. or :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.-mh:font facename=default size=0x0. options so that no ugly VIO window
appears&per. Here is an example :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.NETSCAPE&per.CMD:font facename=default size=0x0.&colon.

:cgraphic.@echo off
rem do some initialization here, e&per.g&per. change directory
cd D&colon.\WebStuff
rem now call Netscape
netscape&per.exe
rem now the &per.cmd file is put to sleep until Netscape is
rem terminated; subsequent calls to NETSCDDE will contact
rem this running Netscape instance
rem after Netscape is terminated, execute this&colon.
call cleanup&per.cmd
rem or whatever you want
:ecgraphic.
:p.

:p.
Thanks, Marcus de Geus, for this suggestion&per. 
.br
:li.
Here's a trick from Chris Wenham, senior editor of :link reftype=hd res=10157.OS/2
e-zine:elink., found in the :hp2.SmartSuite:ehp2. Mailing List (smartsuite-os2@makelist&per.com)&colon.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.
:p.
"If you need to change the web browser that Smartsuite
apps call when you click one of their Internet buttons
(like Organizer's button to go to the Almanack page),
or send the URL to the currently running copy of Netscape
instead of launching a new instance, you need to do
this&colon. 
:p.
Launch REGEDIT2&per.EXE in the /OS2/SYSTEM directory&per.
Expand the HKEY_CLASSES_ROOT tree&per. Scroll down to
"http" and expand it all the way down (through "shell"
and "open") until you come to "command"&per. 
:p.
Right click on the data in the "(Default)" key, pick
"Modify", and change the path to the new browser, making
sure it's followed with a "%1" (which represents the
URL)&per. Close RegEdit&per. 
:p.
You shouldn't need to reboot, but you might need to
restart any SS components that are running&per.:font facename=default size=0x0. 
:p.
Chris then states that you can enter NETSCDDE&per.EXE
as your browser in this section&per. 
:eol.
:p.

.br

