:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XWPSound:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.

:artwork name='config_8sounds.bmp' runin align=left.XWorkplace can :hp2.enhance the "Sound" object:ehp2. by replacing
the "Sound" page in that object to allow changing and
organizing system sounds more easily&per. 
:p.
In order to use this feature, you need to have the :hp2.XWPSound:ehp2.
replacement class installed&per. 
:p.
The main enhancement to the "Sound" page is the support
for :hp2."sound schemes",:ehp2. which IBM half-introduced with
OS/2 Warp 4&per. The main problem with sound schemes
was however that it was nearly impossible to define
one's own schemes without messing with the system INI
files directly&per. 
:p.
XWorkplace's new "Sound" page has a new interface which
allows you to quickly select a sound scheme, save your
current system sounds as a new sound scheme, and delete
existing schemes&per. I have designed this interface
to be similar to that of Windows 95, which, in this
one case, I consider quite well done&per. Since the
new "Sound" page handles sound schemes already, the
original "Sound schemes" page is no longer displayed&per.
:hp2.
:p.
Warp 3 users:ehp2. might be happy to find out that these sound
schemes now work on their operating system too&per.
To be more precise, the "Sound" page lets you :hp1.organize:ehp1.
your sounds on Warp 3 as well; however, you still won't
get sound scheme support in your Layout Palette (which,
on Warp 4 and higher, allows you to specify different
sounds for each folder)&per. 
:p.
Press :hp2."Help":ehp2. on the new "Sound" page to receive more
detailed instructions&per. :hp2.
:p.
Note&colon.:ehp2. System sounds are stored in the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.MMPM&per.INI:font facename=default size=0x0.
file in your :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.MMOS2:font facename=default size=0x0. directory, while sound schemes (for
some reason only IBM knows) are stored in :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.OS2SYS&per.INI:font facename=default size=0x0.&per.
I have stuck to this in order not to break compatibility&per.
As a consequence, however, all users on your system
share the same system sounds and sound schemes, even
if you have different Desktops (and :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.OS2&per.INI:font facename=default size=0x0. files)
for each user&per. Sorry, complain at IBM (as if that
helped)&per. 
:p.
The "Sound" object replacement works regardless of whether
you have enabled the new system sounds (see the :link reftype=hd res=10090.next
page:elink.)&per. 
:p.
If you want the "Sound" object replacement only, without
the new system sounds, disable "Extended system sounds"
feature on the "Features" page of the :link reftype=hd res=10083."XWorkplace Setup"
object&per.:elink. 
:p.
To disable the "Sound" object replacement, deregister
the XWPSound class from the :link reftype=hd res=10083."XWorkplace Setup" object&per.:elink.

.br

.* Source file: "mm_2sounds.html"
:h2 res=10090 x=right width=70%.New System Sounds
:p.
:hp2.Classes&colon. XFolder, XFldDesktop:ehp2.:cgraphic.________________________________________________________________________________:ecgraphic.
:p.
If you have the OS/2 multimedia subsystem (MMPM/2) with
any sound card installed, XWorkplace can play additional
system sounds on certain occasions, just as older XFolder
versions did already&per. 
:p.
If you enable the "Extended system sounds" in "XWorkplace
Setup", XWorkplace will add new events to the "Sound"
page in the "Sound" object&per. 
:p.
Please note that the XWorkplace system sounds will make
your system slower, just as the regular system sounds
do too&per. Even on my Pentium-133 with 32 MB RAM, this
is noticeable, even though XWorkplace uses a separate
thread to play its sounds&per. 
:p.
Configuring these new sounds is not too spectacular&colon.
XWorkplace just adds a few more items to the events
list box on the "Sounds" page&per. All the XWorkplace
items start with "XWorkplace", so you'll be able to
view them grouped together&per. 
:p.
You can find a few small sounds in the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WAV:font facename=default size=0x0. subdirectory
of the XWorkplace installation directory to get you
started&per. :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.;-):font facename=default size=0x0. :hp2.
:p.
Implementation&per.:ehp2. To introduce these features, several
components of XWorkplace are interacting&per. To intercept
system events for the new system sounds, the XFolder
and XFldDesktop classes need to be installed&per. However,
the new XWPSound class replacement (see the :link reftype=hd res=10089.previous
page:elink.) is not required for the new system sounds&per.
That class only makes configuration easier&per. 
.br

