.* Source file: "ctr_1intro.html"
:h2 res=10091 x=right width=70%.Introduction
:p.
Starting with V0&per.9&per.7, XWorkplace contains a
replacement to OS/2 Warp 4's WarpCenter&per. This is
called the "XCenter"&per. 
:p.
Technically, this is not a WarpCenter replacement&per.&per.&per.
it does not replace the "SmartCenter" WPS class, since
that class is completely undocumented in the first place&per.
Instead, the XCenter is a new implementation from scratch&per.
It is not compatible with the WarpCenter and does not
take over its settings, but it can do pretty much the
same&per.&per.&per. and more&per. 
:p.
Compared to the WarpCenter, the XCenter offers you the
following advantages&colon. 
:ul compact.:li.
It is :hp2.fully configurable&per.:ehp2. You can add items to the
XCenter at your free will, while the WarpCenter will
always contain fixed items at fixed locations&per. 
:p.
The items in the XCenter are called "widgets"&per. You
can add widgets to the XCenter in any order&per. 
:p.
See :link reftype=hd res=10092."Adding and removing widgets":elink. for details&per. 
.br
:li.
You can have :hp2.more than one XCenter:ehp2. on your system&per.
Each XCenter stores its widgets and their settings separately
so that they will never conflict&per. 
.br
:li.
The XCenter offers you :hp2.more display styles:ehp2. than the
WarpCenter&per. You can drag and drop fonts and colors
onto the widgets, which will retain these settings individually&per.
Besides, the XCenter has an "auto-hide" option so that
it will reduce itself to a tiny bar at the bottom of
the screen, similar to the task bar on Windows 95&per.
You can set those display options in the XCenter's settings
notebook&per. 
.br
:li.
The XCenter supports :hp2.plug-in DLLs&per.:ehp2. Any programmer
can add new widget types to the XCenter by writing a
DLL and put it into the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.plugins\xcenter:font facename=default size=0x0. directory of
the XWorkplace installation directory&per. 
:p.
See :link reftype=hd res=10094."About plug-in DLLs":elink. for details&per. 
.br
:li.
The XCenter runs on a :hp2.separate thread:ehp2. within the WPS
and can thus run with a higher priority than other programs&per.
You can set the priority in the XCenter's settings notebook&per.

:p.
While this cannot fix the PM single input queue (SIQ)
problems, this can still give you access to the XCenter
if some program uses up all CPU time&per. 
:eul.
:p.

.* Source file: "ctr_2addwgt.html"
:h2 res=10092 x=right width=70%.Adding and Removing Widgets
:p.
To :hp2.add a new widget:ehp2. to the XCenter, right-click on an
empty space on the XCenter bar and select :hp2."Add widget"&per.:ehp2.
A submenu appears which lists all available widget types&per.
Select one from that list, and a new widget will appear
in the XCenter&per. 
:p.
The contents of that menu will depend on whether widgets
have already been added to the XCenter and how many
plug-in DLLs are contained in the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.plugins\xcenter:font facename=default size=0x0. directory
of the XWorkplace installation directory&per. 
:p.
The exception to this rule are the "object button" widgets,
which represent any Desktop object&per. These widgets
can be used to display the contents of a folder (similar
to XFolder's :link reftype=hd res=10044.folder content menus:elink.), if the object is
a folder, or to quick-start an object in its default
view, if the object is not a folder&per. 
:p.
In order to add such an object button widget, simply
drag the object onto the XCenter, like this&colon. 
.br

:artwork name='ctr_drag.bmp' runin align=left.
:p.
To :hp2.remove a widget:ehp2. again, right-click on it and select
"Remove widget" from the widget's context menu&per.

.br

.* Source file: "ctr_3stdwgt.html"
:h2 res=10093 x=right width=70%.Standard Widgets
:p.
Per default, the XCenter comes with the following widget
types&colon. 
:ul compact.:li.
The :hp2."X-Button":ehp2. widget&per. This displays the XWorkplace
"X" logo on the XCenter bar&per. If you click on that
button, a menu opens which gives you access to the "Suspend",
"Restart Desktop", and XShutdown features&per. In addition,
this displays the folder contents of the Desktop&per.

.br

:artwork name='ctr_x.bmp' runin align=left.
.br
:li.
:hp2.Object buttons&per.:ehp2. These represent any Desktop object&per.
These widgets are not displayed in the "Add widgets"
menu&per. To add such a widget, simply drag it onto
the XCenter bar, as shown on the :link reftype=hd res=10092.previous page:elink.&per.

:p.
If the object is a folder, it will display its contents,
if you click on it, similar to the XFolder :link reftype=hd res=10044.folder content
menus:elink.&colon. 
.br

:artwork name='ctr_obj.bmp' runin align=left.
.br
:li.
The :hp2."CPU load":ehp2. widget can also be seen in the above
screenshot and presents the current CPU load as a per-cent
value&per. In addition, it maintains a graph of past
CPU activity&per. 
.br
:li.
Then there are several monitor widgets which display
system information&per. Presently, we have a :hp2.clock:ehp2. and
a :hp2."free memory" widget&colon.:ehp2. 
.br

:artwork name='ctr_mem.bmp' runin align=left.
.br
:li.
Finally, the :hp2."Window list":ehp2. widget displays the contents
of the PM window list&per. As opposed to that list,
the currently active window is shown as a pushed-down
button, and you can click on the items to active the
corresponding window&per. Besides, the window list supports
filtering (right-click on the window list and select
"Properties")&per. 
.br

:artwork name='ctr_winlist.bmp' runin align=left.
:eul.
:p.

.* Source file: "ctr_9plugin.html"
:h2 res=10094 x=right width=70%.About Plug-In DLLs
:p.
The XCenter was designed to support plug-in DLLs&per.
This allows programmers to add new widget types (called
"widget classes") to the XCenter without having to actually
modify XWorkplace itself&per. 
:p.
As an example, let's say you are the developer of an
e-mail program&per. You could write a plug-in that periodically
checks the user's mail server for new mail&per. If any
is found, that widget could start flashing, and if the
user clicks on it, the e-mail client would be started
to retrieve the new mail&per. 
:p.
An XCenter widget is basically a PM window class, so
anybody who has written a PM program before should be
able to write an XCenter plug-in DLL&per. You do :hp1.not:ehp1.
need to know WPS and/or SOM programming&per. 
:p.
For details, please refer to the :link reftype=hd res=10020.Writing XCenter plugins:elink.
section&per. 
.br

