.* Source file: "faq_01general.html"
:h2 res=10095 x=right width=70%.FAQ: General Questions
:p.
First of all&colon. look into the :link reftype=hd res=10083."Workplace Shell":elink.
object, where you will find a lot of useful levers to
make XWorkplace behave&per. 
:p.
If you don't find the answer to your question here,
please look at XWorkplace's :link reftype=hd res=10025.web homepage:elink. also&per. I
am now maintaining a public bug list, which might answer
your question too&per. 
:ol compact.:li.
:hp2.Does XWorkplace slow down the WPS?:ehp2. 
:p.
Depends&per. Some features might cause a bit of a slowdown,
such as the first opening of a folder context menu,
since XWorkplace will have to read in the contents of
the Configuration Folder (including all subfolders)
to build the context menu accordingly&per. 
:p.
By contrast, some other features will actually speed
up the WPS&per. For example, the :link reftype=hd res=10049."Turbo folders":elink. feature
can dramatically speed up folders&per. Also, if extended
file associations are enabled, folder populating is
much faster because XWorkplace is using very efficient
caching routines for object handles internally&per.

:p.
Also, as opposed to some other WPS enhancers, XWorkplace
doesn't use excessive amounts of memory&per. I have
checked this once on my system, and in addition to the
size of the XWorkplace DLLs themselves, XWorkplace only
keeps a few 100 KBs of memory allocated and dynamically
frees storage when it's no longer needed&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.Why are the new system sounds not playing?:ehp2. 
:p.
You will need to install them first&per. See the :link reftype=hd res=10090.corresponding
page:elink. for more&per. 
:p.
Some people reported that after upgrading their sound
cards, XWorkplace's system sounds no longer works&per.
This turned out to be a problem with the multimedia
setup&per. Open the standard "Multimedia Configuration"
object, "Digital Audio" page, and make sure that the
"WAV" file extension appears in the extensions associations
list&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.Why do I keep getting crashes in SOM&per.DLL?:ehp2. 
:p.
If you're using :hp2.VisualAge C++:ehp2. or any other software
which installs SOM runtimes, make sure that :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.SOM&per.DLL:font facename=default size=0x0.
is loaded from :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.\OS2\DLL:font facename=default size=0x0.&per. This DLL has been updated
with more recent Warp fixpaks&per. VAC++ puts additional
directories at the beginning of the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.LIBPATH:font facename=default size=0x0. statement
in :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.CONFIG&per.SYS:font facename=default size=0x0., which still causes the old DLL to
be loaded&per. Put those directories behind :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.\OS2\DLL:font facename=default size=0x0.
in the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.LIBPATH:font facename=default size=0x0.&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.Why do I get Desktop restarts when I change media in
removeable drives (MO, ZIP, &per.&per.&per.)?:ehp2. 
:p.
I have no idea&per. Several people have reported very
strange WPS behavior when a drive folder is opened after
removeable media has been exchanged&per. After that,
the WPS works fine again (until the media is exchanged
again)&per. 
:p.
Note that I do not have removeable drives, other than
a CD-ROM drive and a CD writer&per. I therefore cannot
reproduce these problems here&per. If somebody can take
a look at XWorkplace's source code to find out what
might cause this, this would be a great help&per. 
:p.
IBM has introduced some new removeable media support
with Warp 4 Fixpak 6, so maybe we have a problem there&per.
Christian Hennecke <christian&per.hennecke@ruhr-uni-bochum&per.de>
wrote in some newsgroup that replacing :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.PMWP&per.DLL:font facename=default size=0x0.
with a pre-fixpak 6 version appears to help&per. You'll
also have to install NEWDASD, which should still be
available on Hobbes and Leo&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.Why do XWorkplace's features only work with some folders
and not with others?:ehp2. 
:p.
This is tricky&per. Some people have reported this in
all variations, i&per.e&per. hotkeys work for the Desktop
only, or not in URL folders, or not in Group Folders
(an IBM EWS utility), etc&per.pp&per.&per. The same
applies to status bars&per. 
:p.
From what I can see, this is related to folder subclassing&per.
XWorkplace needs certain window messages to introduce
these features, and if some other WPS class intercepts
these messages, XWorkplace's features behave funny or
cause crashes or do simply not work&per. 
:p.
In general, the more WPS class replacements you have
installed, the more likely these errors are likely to
appear&per. With a "clean" WPS, XWorkplace usually works
fine, but the people who have reported these errors
sometimes had four folder class replacements installed,
and it's really difficult for me to track down these
errors then&per. Try to de-install some WPS extensions
which you don't absolutely need&per. 
:p.
Also, the more messed up your INI files are, the more
likely the WPS is going to become unstable in general&per.
I strongly recommend Henk Kelder's :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WPTOOLS:font facename=default size=0x0. package,
which you should run from time to time anyway, to clean
up the INI files&per. This is still continually updated
and available at Hobbes&per. 
:p.
I have also found that installation order is important&per.
Some WPS extensions seem to simply "swallow" messages
which they don't need, assuming that they are the only
WPS extension on the system&per. (This might apply to
XWorkplace also, but I have tried to avoid this&per.)
Now, if XWorkplace comes before this greedy WPS extension
in the WPS class replacement list, which is the case
if XWorkplace was installed first, it does get the message
before the other WPS extension&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.Does XWorkplace cooperate with Object Desktop?:ehp2. 
:p.
In theory, yes&per. Practically, sometimes&per. For
details about this (and for other WPS utilities also),
see the separate :link reftype=hd res=10035."Compatibility":elink. page&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.Why do I hear the disk drives running every time I open
the "Drives" folder?:ehp2. 
:p.
The reason for this is that the XWorkplace status bars
query the free space on a drive&per. If the first object
in your "Drives" folder represents a floppy drive, it's
this drive that's queried&per. 
:p.
To avoid this, change the status bar information for
WPDisk objects in the "Workplace Shell" object, page
2 of "Status bars"&per. Then this information will not
be queried&per. 
:p.
Alternatively, you can disable status bars for the "Drives"
folder only on the "XFolder" page in the Drives folder's
settings notebook&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.Does XWorkplace run on Macintosh systems?:ehp2. 
:p.
No&per. 
:eol.
:p.
Shameless self-advertisement&colon. XWorkplace cooperates
perfectly with the fantastic :hp2.CommandPak:ehp2. from the same
author, available also at :link reftype=hd res=10100.xworkplace&per.org:elink.&per. This
package will improve the OS/2 command line dramatically,
among others offering some WPS support from the command
line also&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "faq_02install.html"
:h2 res=10096 x=right width=70%.FAQ: Installation Questions
:p.

:ol compact.:li.
:hp2.The WPS crashes/keeps rebooting after the Desktop restart&per.
What is this?:ehp2. 
:p.
Difficult to say&per. If it keeps rebooting, this is
a sure sign that the WPS is trapping, i&per.e&per. exceptions
occur when it's booting up&per. Same thing as on the
:link reftype=hd res=10095.previous page:elink., XWorkplace seems to be conflicting with
other WPS extensions&per. 
:p.
Otherwise, it might simply be that restarting the WPS
is not working on your system&per. The Desktop restart
is only intended as a shortcut, but if it doesn't work,
try rebooting instead&per. 
:p.
Some people have reported that removing XWorkplace INI
keys seems to help&per. Take some INI editor and look
in OS2&per.INI for application names starting with "XFolder"&per.
Delete them all&per. XWorkplace does not :hp1.rely:ehp1. on INI
keys any more&per. This will delete all your settings
and reset the language to English, but maybe XWorkplace
will run&per. 
:p.
In addition, it is always recommended to have more recent
OS/2 fixpaks applied, that is, at least Fixpak 35 for
Warp 3 and fixpak 5 for Warp 4&per. XWorkplace will
run without fixpaks, but this might lead to problems&per.
IBM has changed many things with the SOM kernel over
time, which the WPS uses for its class management&per.
I have tried my best to enhance compatibility, but I
cannot test all possible configurations myself&per.
I have found, for example, that the standard Warp 3
SOM kernel is extremely buggy, so at least for Warp
3 I :hp1.strongly:ehp1. recommend applying fixpaks&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.What OS/2 versions and fixpak levels has XWorkplace
been tested on?:ehp2. 
:p.
See :link reftype=hd res=10034."Requirements"&per.:elink. 
:eol.
:p.

.br

.* Source file: "faq_03menus.html"
:h2 res=10097 x=right width=70%.FAQ: Menu Questions
:p.

:ol compact.:li.
:hp2.My menus have become so crowded&per. What can I do?:ehp2.

:p.
If you consider your :hp2.context menus too crowded,:ehp2. you
can tell the WPS to omit displaying those menu entries
which are only "doubles" to mouse operations ("Copy",
"Move", etc&per.)&per. 
:ul compact.
.br
:li.
On Warp 3, putting a :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.SET MENUSTYLE=SHORT:font facename=default size=0x0. into :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.CONFIG&per.SYS:font facename=default size=0x0.
will do the job&per. 
.br
:li.
On Warp 4 and higher, there is a new setting in the
"System" object in the "System Setup" folder&per. You
should find it on the "Menu" tab&per. This setting is
also found in every folder's own settings notebook;
there is also folder Setup String to set this for folders
individually&per. See :link reftype=hd res=10146."WPFolder Setup Strings":elink. for more&per.

:eul.
:p.
Moreover, you can remove many default menu items individually
in the :link reftype=hd res=10083."Workplace Shell":elink. object on the "Context menu"
pages&per. 
:p.
The :hp2.folder content functions:ehp2. are helpful, but can crowd
your context menus too much also if you declare many
folders to be your favorites&per. On my system, I have
created a separate folder called "frequent", which I
have declared to be my only favorite folder&per. In
this folder, I can put all those folders which I frequently
access, so I only have one context menu entry, but a
submenu with all my favorite folders&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.When I select a context menu item, not the XWorkplace
function, but some other function gets executed&per.
What is this?:ehp2. 
:p.
Probably a menu ID conflict with some other WPS extension&per.
This is a known problem with Network logins&per. Go
to the "XWorkplace Configuration", "Paranoia" page,
and raise the "Menu item ID offset"&per. Press "Help"
there for details&per. With V0&per.9&per.0, the default
offset has been raised to 700, which should help in
most cases&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.When I select a non-XWorkplace context menu item, XWorkplace
still executes one of its own functions&per. What is
this?:ehp2. 
:p.
Same thing as above&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.When I open a context menu, my system crashes/hangs&per.
What can I do?:ehp2. 
:p.
Versions prior to V0&per.82 served as a test for video
drivers in this respect&per. ;-) I have found out that
some video drivers do not support transparent background
mix for bitmaps, which XFolder used to use&per. While
some drivers silently ignored the transparency, other
drivers crashed badly and stopped the whole system (especially
Matrox Millenium)&per. With V0&per.82, I have changed
the icon painting for folder content menus to use regular
icons instead of bitmaps&per. Icon painting is still
disabled per default in case something should still
go wrong&per. Turn on "Show icons" on the "Context menus"
pages in "Workplace Shell" to enable icon painting&per.

:p.
If you still have problems, Ralph Scharpf reported that
one could install the IBM GRADD drivers for MGA video
cards instead, which appear to be working&per. Unfortunately,
those cards do not support 1024x768 with more than 60
Hz, but if you can live with 800x600, this appears to
be a solution&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.Why do folder content menus not work with folders on
the Launchpad?:ehp2. 
:p.
Because the Launchpad is not a folder&per. XWorkplace
can only subclass the default folder window procedure
to receive important system messages when menus are
being opened, which is when the variable menu items
are inserted into context menus&per. Since the Launchpad
does not use the folder's default window procedure,
XWorkplace cannot easily subclass it either&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.I have added something to the config folder, but it
doesn't appear in the menus&per. Is this a compatibility
conflict?:ehp2. 
:p.
Probably no&per. Since V0&per.70, XWorkplace uses the
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.&per.ICONPOS:font facename=default size=0x0. extended attributes of the config folder
and its subfolders to determine the order of objects
in a folder&per. Trouble is, these are only written
by the WPS when the folder is closed, and only if the
folder was open in Icon or Details view&per. So simply
open the folder in Details view and close it again&per.
That should work&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.How do I get the underlined characters in menu items
for keyboard shortcuts?:ehp2. 
:p.
Put a tilde character (:font facename='Courier' size=18x12."~":font facename=default size=0x0.) in front of a certain character
in the program object's title&per. This will underline
the following character in the menu entry, allowing
you to type this character as a keyboard shortcut when
the context menu is displayed&per. 
:p.
(This is different from the :link reftype=hd res=10053.folder hotkeys:elink. which XWorkplace
adds to open folders&per.) 
:p.
Example&colon. :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.OS/2 ~command window:font facename=default size=0x0. will make "c" a
keyboard shortcut in the context menu&per. 
:p.
For this, be sure to check "Suppress ''~'' in window
title" in the :link reftype=hd res=10083."Workplace Shell":elink. object on the "Context
menus" pages&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.I have added a program object to the config folder,
but when I select the menu item, I get error messages
from the program&per. What am I doing wrong?:ehp2. 
:p.
You will probably need to put a :font facename='Courier' size=18x12."%":font facename=default size=0x0. character into the
"Parameters" field of the program object to prevent
XWorkplace from passing the folder as a parameter&per.
See the context help for the XWorkplace Configuration
Folder for details&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.I have added a shadow to the config folders, but opening
it doesn't work like with the other objects&per. What
am I doing wrong?:ehp2. 
:p.
XWorkplace does open shadows of program objects in the
configuration folders, but it does not change their
directories or parameters&per. This is not a bug, it's
an intentional limitation for security&per. COPY your
program objects to the configuration folders instead
of creating shadows&per. See the context help for the
XWorkplace Configuration Folder for details&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.How can I execute CMD&per.EXE commands?:ehp2. 
:p.
For commands which are built into CMD&per.EXE (such
as :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.REN:font facename=default size=0x0., :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.COPY:font facename=default size=0x0., :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DEL:font facename=default size=0x0., :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.CD:font facename=default size=0x0.), put a program object into the
XWorkplace Configuration Folder&per. Then specify :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.CMD&per.EXE:font facename=default size=0x0.
in the program object with :font facename='Courier' size=18x12./C <commands>:font facename=default size=0x0. in the
"Parameters" field&per. 
:p.
Example for deleting the folder's whole content&colon.
put :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.CMD&per.EXE:font facename=default size=0x0. in the "Path and filename" field and
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12./C DEL *:font facename=default size=0x0. in the "Parameters" field&per. This is, of
course, just a stupid example and NOT recommended&per.

.br
:li.
:hp2.How can I use REXX for WPS manipulation?:ehp2. 
:p.
I have included extra information in the appendices
of this documentation, which might be useful to you&colon.

:ul compact.
.br
:li.
a complete list of all the :link reftype=hd res=10146.WPFolder settings strings:elink.;

.br
:li.
a collection of OS/2's default :link reftype=hd res=10145.Object ID's:elink.&per. 
.br
:li.
a diagram of the :link reftype=hd res=10099.WPS Class Hierarchy:elink.&per. 
:eul.
:p.
If you're not too familiar with REXX, you can copy and
modify the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.ALWSSORT&per.CMD:font facename=default size=0x0. file in the XWorkplace installation
directory to test some of the folder settings&per. Please
see the :link reftype=hd res=10017."Related files":elink. page for more&per. 
:p.
In addition, I strongly recommend the INF book "Rexx
Tips&amp.Tricks" by Bernd Schemmer, which is available
as "rxtt28&per.zip" (or newer) on Hobbes&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.Why can't I open my new config folder object more than
once?:ehp2. 
:p.
If you create programs objects which need to be opened
several times from different directories (namely for
command line objects), be sure to check the "Create
new window" flag on the "Window" tab in the object's
notebook&per. Otherwise OS/2 will not start a new window
but simply resurface the already opened one&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.I have deleted the XWorkplace Configuration Folder&per.
How do I get it back?:ehp2. 
:p.
With V0&per.9&per.1, this behavior has changed because
many people have complained about XFolder's behavior
when the Configuration Folder was missing&per. So to
recreate that folder, go to the "Object" page in the
:link reftype=hd res=10083."XWorkplace Setup" object:elink. and press the respective button&per.

:eol.
:p.

.br

.* Source file: "faq_04shutdwn.html"
:h2 res=10098 x=right width=70%.FAQ: XShutdown Questions
:p.

:ol compact.:li.
:hp2.Why does automatic reboot not work on my system?:ehp2. 
:p.
I don't know, on some systems it just doesn't, for example
my Warp 3 with FixPak 35, but it does on my Warp 4&per.
I was unable to figure out what the reason for this
is, but a few users have also reported this, and the
problem also occurs with the WarpEnhancer reboot feature,
so I guess it's not XWorkplace's fault&per. (The reboot
feature uses an undocumented IOCtl to :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DOS&per.SYS:font facename=default size=0x0. anyway,
so there is probably no guarantee by IBM that it will
always work&per.) If you have the IBM BootManager installed,
you can circumvent this problem by specifying :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.SETBOOT&per.EXE:font facename=default size=0x0.
as a user reboot option (Desktop settings notebook ->
"XDesktop" page 1 -> "Actions")&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.Is there anything which XShutdown does not properly
save?:ehp2. 
:p.
Yes&per. XShutdown does not save positions of folders
which have changed just before XShutdown was initiated,
because the WPS :hp1.delays:ehp1. saving folder positions in some
background thread to which I have found no access, and
the format of the folder position entries in OS2&per.INI
is not documented, so I cannot do it myself&per. The
same applies to folders which are closed by XShutdown
itself&per. If you want folder positions to be saved,
close them manually and wait a few (about 10-20) seconds
before starting XShutdown&per. 
:p.
(With "folder positions", I mean the position of an
open folder :hp1.window:ehp1. itself, not the positions of the
icons in a folder&per. These are properly saved&per.)

:p.
Also, XShutdown cannot save changes to the Tasklist
window (e&per.g&per. fonts or colors being dropped on
them)&per. If you want these changes saved, you'll have
to use OS/2's regular shutdown just once&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.Why do I keep getting errors while the INI files are
being saved?:ehp2. 
:p.
This is one of the all time favorites, and the problem
has changed with several releases&per. 
:ul compact.:li.
With early versions :hp2.before XFolder 0&per.85,:ehp2. this was
mostly due to INI keys which do not contain any data,
which shouldn't happen&per. This has been fixed a long
while ago&per. 
.br
:li.
Still, many people reported these errors to occur pretty
randomly, even with INI keys which :hp1.do:ehp1. contain data&per.
I was finally able to track this down to occur with
pretty large INI files&per. I suspect that basically
the problem sits in PM itself, since the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WinGetLastError:font facename=default size=0x0.
API frequently returns :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.PMERR_MEMORY_ALLOCATION_ERR:font facename=default size=0x0.,
which is cooly described in the PM reference with "An
error occured during memory management&per."&per. I
believe that with large INI files, PM runs out of shared
memory, which is used for INI file management&per. The
limit above which the errors start to occur is dependent
on how much shared memory is already used on the respective
machine, but it's usually way above 1 MB per INI file&per.

:p.
Basically, :hp2.before V0&per.9&per.5,:ehp2. XWorkplace used PrfOpenProfile
to create a new INI file (for the user and system INI
file, respectively) and then went through all applications
and keys in the profile and simply copied them&per.
This caused quite some stress on the PM shared memory
management&per. 
:p.
Reducing the size of the INI files did help&per. By
the way, it was not only XShutdown which fails on these
INIs, but any other application which copies the user
and system profiles bytewise also (I've checked this
with WPSBackup once, which just crashes)&per. 
:p.
To reduce the size of the INIs, first of all, run CHECKINI
(from Henk Kelder's WPTOOLS package) to have all invalid
entries removed&per. In addition, use any INI editor
to manually delete the following keys which can grow
very large :hp1.(make a backup of your INIs before doing
this)&colon.:ehp1. 
:ul compact.:li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.PM_Abstract&colon.Icons:font facename=default size=0x0.&colon. this contains the icons
for all abstract objects&per. By deleting this key,
you will lose all user-defined icons for abstract objects,
but in many cases, the data in here is redundant, because
e&per.g&per. program objects use the executable's icon
per default anyway&per. :li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.PM_Workplace&colon.FolderPos:font facename=default size=0x0.&colon. this holds the window
positions of all the folders that were ever opened by
the WPS, even if a folder was last opened five years
ago&per. You will lose all your folder positions when
deleting this, but except for maybe a dozen folders
this should be acceptable, and for those, you can quickly
resize them again&per. 
:eul.
:p.
:li.
With :hp2.V0&per.9&per.5,:ehp2. I have rewritten the routines so
the PM APIs are no longer used for creating the new
profiles&per. Since Carsten Arnold told me the file
format of the INI files, I wrote a set of routines which
write these without using shared memory&per. Apparently,
this helped&per. This is the "new method" which is now
selectable on the "XShutdown" page in the Desktop's
settings notebook&per. 
:eul.
:p.

.br
:li.
:hp2.After using Xhutdown, at the next reboot, the screen
is reset to VGA, and I get a dialog saying that the
Desktop could not be found&per. What is this?:ehp2. 
:p.
This is the same problem as described in the previous
question&per. Obviously, your INI files have not been
properly saved&per. As a result, OS/2 reverts to default
values for the screen and cannot find your desktop&per.

:p.
If this happens, you will find a backup copy of both
OS2&per.INI and OS2SYS&per.INI in your \OS2 directory,
renamed to &per.BAK&per. Before XShutdown saves the
INI files, it renames the old ones&per. Boot to a command
line (using Alt-F1 during startup) and rename these
two backups back to *&per.INI&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.Why is APM power-off is not working on my system?:ehp2. 
:p.
I don't know&per. On some systems, it just doesn't&per.
I'm pretty sure it's not XWorkplace's fault because
XWorkplace does nothing but calling into the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.APM&per.SYS:font facename=default size=0x0.
device driver, after which it has no control over what
that driver is doing to power off the system&per. 
:p.
IBM updated the APM APM support with Warp 4 Fixpak 6
(and possibly later too)&per. The "XShutdown" page in
the Desktop's settings notebook displays the version
number of the installed APM driver, which should be
at least 1&per.2 to make APM power-off work&per. 
:p.
Even worse, there are many systems which have no 100%
compatible APM support in the BIOS, and this might be
the problem too&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.APM power-off works, but at the next reboot I am getting
CHKDSKs&per.:ehp2. 
:p.
Again, XWorkplace can't do much about this&per. I am
getting these CHKDSKs too on my laptop, even though
it's working fine on my desktop machine&per. Apparently
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.APM&per.SYS:font facename=default size=0x0. does not wait long enough for some hard
disk with large internal caches to flush their caches
to disk before the system power is killed&per. This
appears to be a generic problem which I've also read
about with Win95, so you'll probably have to disable
APM altogether in this case&per. 
:eol.
:p.

.* Source file: "080related.html"
:h1 res=10017 x=right width=70%.Related Files
:p.
There are a number of files in the different subdirectory
of the XWorkplace installation directory that might
be useful to you&colon. 
:ul compact.:li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.:hp2.BOOTMGR&per.CMD:ehp2.:font facename=default size=0x0. is new with V0&per.83&per. This script
was supplied by Duane A&per. Chamblee <duanec@ibm&per.net>
and will automatically add all the current BootManager
choices to the XWorkplace user-reboot actions for XShutdown&per.
This is done by modifying the XWorkplace keys in OS2&per.INI
directly&per. No guarantee that this will actually work
on your system! 
.br
:li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.:hp2.CROBJxxx&per.CMD:ehp2.:font facename=default size=0x0. (with xxx being a three-digit language
code, as described in :link reftype=hd res=10039.National Language Support:elink.) are
used by XWorkplace to create the default Configuration
Folders&per. These are just plain REXX scripts which
create a number of objects on your desktop&per. 
:p.
These scripts are called both after XWorkplace has been
installed (after the first Desktop restart) and also
whenever XWorkplace fails to locate its Configuration
Folder&per. 
:p.
You may modify these scripts to have a different default
configuration created&per. However, you should be very
careful in changing the various object settings, especially
the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.OBJECTID:font facename=default size=0x0. keywords, because XWorkplace might rely
on these&per. 
.br
:li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.:hp2.NEWOBJ&per.CMD:ehp2.:font facename=default size=0x0. was used in old XFolder versions (before
0&per.52) to create objects&per. This is :link reftype=hd res=10041.now done with
templates,:elink. but this script is still included, for those
who got used to it&per. 
:p.
It needs the following parameters on the command line&colon.

:cgraphic.newobj <wpsclass> <name>
:ecgraphic.
:p.

:p.
It will create a new instance of :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.<wpsclass>:font facename=default size=0x0. with
the title :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.<name>:font facename=default size=0x0. in the current directory&per.
Please see the :link reftype=hd res=10099."WPS Classes" page:elink. for a list of WPS
classes&per. Not all of these make sense when creating
objects though&per. 
:p.
Here's an example&colon. 
:cgraphic.newobj WPFolder New_Folder
:ecgraphic.
:p.

:p.
will create a new folder called "New_Folder" in the
current directory&per. :hp2.
:p.
Note&colon.:ehp2. Since V0&per.41, XFolder can also create
objects from templates&per. This has the advantage that
you can create objects with certain default settings
(namely for folders)&per. 
.br
:li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.:hp2.NETSCDDE&per.EXE:ehp2.:font facename=default size=0x0. (The Netscape DDE Interface)&colon.
see the :link reftype=hd res=10012.separate chapter:elink. in this documentation&per.

.br
:li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.:hp2.REPCLASS&per.EXE:ehp2.:font facename=default size=0x0. was used by old XFolder versions to
register the various XWorkplace class and replace the
standard WPS classes with them&per. It needs the following
parameters on the command line&colon. 
:cgraphic.repclass <oldclass> <replacewithclass> [<dllname>]
:ecgraphic.
:p.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.
:p.
<oldclass>:font facename=default size=0x0. is the WPS class that you wish to replace&per.
This is case-sensitive&per. :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.
:p.
<replacewithclass>:font facename=default size=0x0. is the new WPS class that you
wish to register and at the same time replace :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.<oldclass>:font facename=default size=0x0.
with&per. This is also case-sensitive&per. :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.
:p.
<dllname>:font facename=default size=0x0. is the dynamic link library (DLL) that
contains :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.<replacewithclass>:font facename=default size=0x0.&per. If the DLL is
not on the LIBPATH (as with XFolder), you will need
to specify the full path&per. 
:p.
If :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.<dllname>:font facename=default size=0x0. is omitted, :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.<replacewithclass>:font facename=default size=0x0.
will be de-registered and removed from the replacement
list for :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.<oldclass>:font facename=default size=0x0.&per. 
:p.
Example for XWorkplace itself&colon. the classes to
be replaced are :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WPFolder:font facename=default size=0x0., :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WPDisk:font facename=default size=0x0., and :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WPSystem:font facename=default size=0x0., the
new XFolder classes are :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XFolder:font facename=default size=0x0., :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XFldDisk:font facename=default size=0x0., and :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XFldSystem:font facename=default size=0x0.,
which all reside in the XFLDR&per.DLL file&per. 
:p.
All action performed with this program will only have
an effect after rebooting or restarting the WPS with
WPSRESET&per.EXE (see below)&per. 
.br
:li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.:hp2.SOUNDxxx&per.CMD:ehp2.:font facename=default size=0x0. (with xxx being a three-digit language
code, as described in :link reftype=hd res=10039.National Language Support:elink.) is
automatically run by XWorkplace when the new :link reftype=hd res=10090.system
sounds:elink. are enabled&per. These little scripts will write
a few language-dependent strings into the INI files
of the OS/2 Multimedia Subsystem (MMPM/2), which will
then be visible in the OS/2 "Sound" object&per. Only
if XWorkplace finds these, it will play system sounds
at all&per. 
.br
:li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.:hp2.SOUNDOFF&per.CMD:ehp2.:font facename=default size=0x0. will turn sounds off again by deleting
the respective entries from the MMPM/2 INI files&per.
XWorkplace will then stop playing system sounds&per.
:hp2.
:p.
Note&colon.:ehp2. The :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.SOUND:font facename=default size=0x0. files assume that that your MMPM/2
directory is :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.\MMOS2:font facename=default size=0x0. on your boot drive&per. If it is
not, you must alter the files yourself&per. 
.br
:li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.:hp2.TREESIZE&per.EXE:ehp2.:font facename=default size=0x0. is used by the new default menu item
of the same name and displays the disk usage of a folder
and all its subfolders in a Tree view&per. If Treesize
is started with a directory name as a parameter, this
directory is displayed, or the current directory otherwise&per.

:p.
After Treesize is done with its calculations, you may
drag and drop new WPS folders onto the main window,
whose size will be calculated then also&per. 
:p.
Treesize offers you some settings using context menus&per.

:p.
All settings are saved when Treesize is closed&per.

.br
:li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.:hp2.WPSRESET&per.EXE:ehp2.:font facename=default size=0x0. can restart your WPS without rebooting
your computer altogether (see the :link reftype=hd res=10067."Restart Desktop":elink.
page for details)&per. It is now (V0&per.71) only used
by the install script any more, while XWorkplace does
its own Desktop restarting internally&per. In order
to prevent accidental execution, WPSRESET&per.EXE must
be started with a :font facename='Courier' size=18x12."-D":font facename=default size=0x0. parameter on the command line&per.

.br
:li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.:hp2.XHELP&per.CMD:ehp2.:font facename=default size=0x0. is a powerful REXX script which can display
language-dependent messages, both in HTML and simple
ASCII format&per. It was taken out of the "OS/2 CommandPak"
by the same author, also available at :link reftype=hd res=10100.xworkplace&per.org:elink.&per.
In that package, you will find extensive documentation
of xhelp&per. 
:p.
In XWorkplace's context, xhelp was previously used by
the text-mode install program&per. XWorkplace is now
using WarpIN for installation, so xhelp is only included
any more in case someone still wants to use the text-mode
install&per. 
.br
:li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.:hp2.XSHUTDWN&per.EXE:ehp2.:font facename=default size=0x0. has been removed with V0&per.9&per.7&per.

.br
:li.
:hp2.All the other &per.CMD files:ehp2. in the XWorkplace directory
are REXX scripts used by the default XWorkplace configuration
to quickly set certain folder settings (they can be
found in the "Quick Settings" submenu)&per. The scripts
are very similar, varying only in the settings that
are applied to a folder&per. ALWSSORT&per.CMD is commented,
so you can look through it and see what it is doing&per.
Copy ALWSSORT&per.CMD to some other filename and change
the settings that are applied to the folder in order
to apply customized settings to folders&per. 
:eul.
:p.

