.* Source file: "further_1WPSClasses.html"
:h2 res=10126 x=right width=70%.What Are WPS Classes?
:p.

:p.
In general, in object-oriented programming, a :hp2.class:ehp2.
is an abstract definition of both (1&per.) data types
and (2&per.) actions that can be performed on that data&per.
The latter are commonly known as object :hp2.methods:ehp2.&per.

:p.
While classes only describe an object type in an abstract
way, the objects that really exist in a program are
called :hp2.instances:ehp2. of a certain class&per. 
:p.
Take a WPS program object, for example&colon. every
program object is an instance of the class WPProgram,
defined by the WPS&per. The (1&per.) data of the program
object would be, among others, the executable associated
with it (e&per.g&per. "CMD&per.EXE"), while (2&per.)
methods (that could be performed on this data) would
be starting the executable (by double-clicking or choosing
the "Open" menu item) or changing the executable in
the settings notebook&per. While you cannot "see" methods
from the user interface, methods are used all the time
internally every time the WPS is doing something&per.
If you're familiar with that term, methods can vaguely
be described as an Application Programmer's Interface
(API) to an object&per. If you know how to program REXX&colon.
every time you use one of those object :link reftype=hd res=10146.setup strings:elink.
to modify an object's data, you're actually calling
a method upon an object&per. 
:p.
Since methods are defined for each class, the methods
that you can call on an object depend on the class of
the object&per. I have not counted them, but already
WPObject, the most basic WPS class, defines more than
100 methods&per. 
:p.
What makes object-oriented programming so flexible (and
popular) is that you can define relationships between
classes&per. In order to understand this, the following
two concepts are helpful&colon. 
:ul compact.:li.
:hp2.Inheritance&per.:ehp2. This concept allows you to define an
object class that takes over all its data types and
methods from another object class, without requiring
that the programmer know how the original class was
actually programmed&per. You can simple "take over"
the features of an existing class and rewrite only what
you wish to implement&per. The original class is then
called the "ancestor" or "parent" of the "descendant"
class&per. 
:p.
For example, with the Workplace Shell, the Desktop class
(called "WPDesktop") is derived from the folder class
(called "WPFolder"), making the Desktop just a special
type of folder&per. 
:p.
So basically, the Desktop has all the capabilities of
a regular folder&colon. you can put other objects into
it, sort its contents, open a tree or details view,
and so on&per. But in addition, the Desktop class provides
a few more actions&colon. its context menu contains
more items (such as "Shutdown" and "System configuration"),
its notebook has more pages, and so on&per. Obviously,
the Desktop inherits folders' characteristics, but adds
a few more&per. On the other hand side, some folder
characteristics are suppressed&colon. for example, you
cannot close the active Desktop, and it does not have
a title bar&per. 
:p.
The WPS implements a derivative structure such that
all objects are logically grouped and interdependent&per.
On an even more abstract level, all object classes of
the WPS are descendants of a SINGLE CLASS named "WPObject",
which provides certain functions that all Desktop objects
need&colon. mainly the ability to display context menus
and notebooks at all and things like that&per. This
is typical of object-oriented programming; such a global
ancestor class is commonly called the "root class" of
a "class hierarchy"&per. 
:p.
On WPObject, the WPS builds a complete tree of classes
known as the :link reftype=hd res=10099.WPS class hierarchy:elink.&per. You can use the
"WPS Classes" page in XWorkplace's :link reftype=hd res=10082."WPS class list":elink.
object to take a look at this&per. 
:p.
Such a class hierarchy has the advantage that one can
change the characteristics of this root class only,
and all classes which are derived from it will also
change&per. (The disadvantage is -- from a programmer's
point of view -- that building such a class hierarchy
requires a whole lot of planning which data and which
methods are common to which classes, and many times
it turns out that this planning wasn't quite optimal&per.
But once this hierarchy has been built in a thoughtful
way -- which, thanks to IBM, indeed is the case with
the WPS -- the advantages are just superb&per.) 
.br
:li.
:hp2.Polymorphism&per.:ehp2. This concept means that, while using
inheritance, you can REPLACE certain characteristics
of an ancestor class with new ones&per. You can redefine
("override") the original object class's behavior&per.
Now, if a certain method is performed on the descendant,
the newly defined method is called instead of the one
that was defined with the ancestor class&per. 
:p.
Just one of the many examples of this can be seen with
the "Help" menu item which is available in every object's
context menu&per. Selecting the "Extended help" menu
item will result in an object's :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.wpDisplayHelp:font facename=default size=0x0. method
to be called&per. This method is introduced by the by
the WPS root class, WPObject, so that all Desktop objects
can display help&colon. the OS/2 help manager is initialized,
the help window is displayed, etc&per. The actual help
page to be displayed however is overridden (following
the concept of polymorphism) by almost every single
WPS class&per. This way, pressing "Help" in a folder's
context menu will show you something different than
from, say, in a program object's menu&per. 
:eul.
:p.
While inheritance and polymorphism are concepts common
to every object-oriented programming environment (and
also to object-oriented languages, such as C++), the
Workplace Shell is even able to provide their advantages
across several applications&per. The WPS consists of
many DLLs which are in part independent of each other,
and programmer's outside of IBM can extend the WPS using
these features without even having the WPS's source
code, which is not possible with "normal" object-oriented
languages&per. 
:p.
This only works because the WPS uses IBM's own :hp2.System
Object Model (SOM),:ehp2. a complex system which provides
object-oriented programming interfaces even across several
code modules, and even independent of the programming
language&per. SOM is so powerful because classes are
instantiated and maintained at run-time instead of compilation
time&per. 
:p.
This is, by the way, where the WPS class list comes
in&colon. when the WPS is booting up, it creates all
the classes (which, in SOM, are objects too, but this
is a complex issue), and establishes the relationships
between them only at this point&per. Only because of
this is it possible to modify classes without IBM, who
created the originals, even knowing about it&per. 
:p.
Just as a short personal opinion, this is still something
that makes OS/2 unique in today's computer world&per.
While most of its other advantages over other operating
systems, such as its reliable multitasking, are not
that unique any more (e&per.g&per. Linux is pretty good
at that, too), the user interface is still not reached
by any operating system that I know&per. Especially
not Windows 95&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "further_2howwork.html"
:h2 res=10127 x=right width=70%.How Does XWorkplace Work?
:p.
XWorkplace registers and/or replaces a whole number
of WPS classes&per. Take a look at the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.INSTALL&per.CMD:font facename=default size=0x0.
script in the XWorkplace installation directory to find
out more about this&per. 
:p.
The most important XWorkplace class replacements are&colon.

:ol compact.:li.
:hp2.XFolder:ehp2. for regular folders, which contains the main
functionality of XWorkplace, 
.br
:li.
:hp2.XFldDisk:ehp2. for "disk" objects, which appear in the "Drives"
folder, 
.br
:li.
:hp2.XFldObject,:ehp2. the WPS root class, for being able to access
a whole number of WPS internals, and 
.br
:li.
:hp2.XFldDesktop:ehp2. for the new Desktop features, especially
the eXtended Shutdown procedure&per. 
:eol.
:p.
All these classes replace the original WPS classes&per.

:p.
In the sense described on the :link reftype=hd res=10126.previous page:elink., the :hp2.XFolder
class:ehp2. is a descendant of the WPFolder class&per. This
way, it can do everything that a regular folder can&per.
As a new function, it adds new context menu items to
all folders, allows for folder hotkeys, changes the
folder window titles, etc&per. 
:p.
By using polymorphism, XFolder redefines certain WPFolder
methods, as described below&per. 
:p.
However, XFolder is then registered with the WPS as
a WPFolder :hp2.replacement,:ehp2. meaning that the WPS will use
the XFolder class as its standard folder class, instead
of WPFolder&per. In doing so, the WPFolder class is
not any more used directly, but only through its replacement
(and descendant) class, XFolder&per. 
:p.
Some of the WPFolder methods that the :hp2.XFolder class:ehp2.
overrides are (this will probably only of interest for
programmers)&colon. 
:ul compact.:li.
:hp2.:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.wpModifyPopupMenu:font facename=default size=0x0.&colon.:ehp2. This WPObject method is called
by the WPS just before an object's context menu is displayed&per.
Each WPS class adds its own, class-specific menu items
here&per. 
:p.
Since XFolder plays with menus a lot, this is one of
the most important methods which XFolder overrides&per.
In this method, XFolder first calls the parent class's
(WPFolder's) :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.wpModifyPopupMenu:font facename=default size=0x0. to have all the standard
menu items added to the object's context menu&per. 
:p.
It then searches for the XFolder configuration folder
(which must have the object ID :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.<XFOLDER_CONFIG>:font facename=default size=0x0.)
and populates it invisibly&per. Now it goes through
all objects in here, adding submenus and menu items
to the context menu accordingly&per. If the configuration
folder is not found, a message box pops up and an empty
folder with the aforementioned ID is created on the
desktop&per. 
:p.
The same is done for the "Folder content" functions
and "favorite" folders&per. However, these submenus
are only filled with objects after they are opened by
the user; this is done by intercepting the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_INITMENU:font facename=default size=0x0.
message in the subclassed folder frame window procedure
(see below)&per. XFolder also subclasses these submenu
windows (and only these) to be able to paint icons and
to intercept mouse button 2 for opening a folder&per.

:p.
(Please note that "subclassing" here has nothing to
do with WPS classes, but is the Presentation Manager
terminology for using a different message procedure
for an existing window in order to be able to intercept
certain PM messages for that window&per. This is done
using the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WinSubclassWindow:font facename=default size=0x0. API&per.) 
:p.
XFolder also modifies various other menus (such as the
the "Sort" submenu) in this method, if the Global Settings
allow this, and adds other menu items, if these have
been enabled in the Global Settings&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.wpMenuItemSelected:font facename=default size=0x0.&colon.:ehp2. This is called by the WPS
whenever a context menu item is selected by the user&per.

:p.
XFolder checks if one of its own (variable) menu items
was selected; if so, it finds the corresponding object
in the configuration folder and opens it&per. If this
object is of the WPProgram class, XWorkplace performs
the usual tricks on it (see the context help for the
XWorkplace Configuration Folder for details)&per. If
the object is a template, no matter of what WPS class,
it is not opened, but XFolder creates a new object from
it in the current folder (via :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.wpCreateFromTemplate:font facename=default size=0x0.)&per.

:p.
If the selected item is one from the "folder content"
submenus, the corresponding object is simply opened&per.

:p.
If any of the other menu items that XFolder adds to
context menus are selected, XFolder itself will perform
the respective action internally&per. 
:p.
If none of the XFolder menu items was selected, the
parent class's (WPFolder's) :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.wpMenuItemSelected:font facename=default size=0x0. method
is called (in order not to prevent the standard menu
items from functioning)&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.wpMenuItemHelpSelected:font facename=default size=0x0.&colon.:ehp2. This is called by the
WPS whenever you press :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.F1:font facename=default size=0x0. over a context menu item&per.
XFolder will display a proper help page, if necessary&per.

.br
:li.
:hp2.:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.wpFilterPopupMenu:font facename=default size=0x0.&colon.:ehp2. With this method, XFolder removes
those default menu entries from the context menus that
you have specified in the Global Settings&per. (This
method is called by the WPS even before wpModifyPopupMenu,
so first items are removed, then new items are inserted&per.)

.br
:li.
:hp2.:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.wpclsQueryTitle:font facename=default size=0x0.&colon.:ehp2. The string :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XFolder:font facename=default size=0x0. (or whatever
you have specified in the Global Settings) is returned
to give the XFolder class a unique name&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.wpOpen:font facename=default size=0x0.&colon.:ehp2. This routine is called by the WPS every
time a folder (and any other object also) is opened&per.
XFolder needs to override this method to implement a
whole number of features&per. 
:p.
First, the parent method is called to have the folder
view opened&colon. the WPS will create a window with
a container control in it and shows this window&per.

:p.
XFolder then intercepts the frame window handle, with
which it can then modify the folder's window title and
reset it to the folders complete path (if enabled in
the Global Settings)&per. Basically, it's a simple :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WinSetWindowText:font facename=default size=0x0.
call, with just a few calculations to truncate the title
if necessary&per. 
:p.
In this method, XFolder also :hp2.subclasses:ehp2. the folder frame
window in order to be able to handle WM_CHAR messages
for folder hotkeys and lots of other things&per. For
subclassing, this method seemed the best place to me,
since all necessary WPS initializiation stuff has been
done by calling the parent method, but the user cannot
interact with the folder yet, because it will only be
filled with objects ("populated" in WPS terminology)
on a different thread afterwards&per. 
:p.
In the new window procedure, XFolder intercepts all
WM_CHAR messages (which are only passed to the frame
window procedure if they have not yet been processed
by the container already, such as cursor keys) and evaluates
them according to its internal hotkey list, which can
be changed in the Global Settings&per. 
:p.
Subclassing is also needed to introduce folder status
bars; the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_QUERYFRAMECTLCOUNT:font facename=default size=0x0., :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_FORMATFRAME:font facename=default size=0x0., and
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_CALCFRAMERECT:font facename=default size=0x0. messages are intercepted to resize
the folder frame and its container child window according
to the space needed for the folder status bar&per. 
:p.
XFolder also intercepts a few container notification
messages in order to provide the "Auto-scroll Tree views"
feature and update the status bar text if object selections
have been changed by the user&per. 
:p.
In addition, XFolder intercepts various menu messages,
such as :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_INITMENU:font facename=default size=0x0. and :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_MENUSELECT:font facename=default size=0x0., to be able to
handle some menu functions which are not accessible
through regular WPS methods&per. 
:p.
All messages which have no meaning to XFolder are passed
on to the original window procedure&per. 
:p.
The :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.wpOpen:font facename=default size=0x0. method is also needed for implementing the
XFolder extended sort functions; XFolder updates the
container settings according to the sort criteria which
you have specified&per. 
.br
:li.
:hp2.:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.wpAddSettingsPages:font facename=default size=0x0.&colon.:ehp2. This method is called by the
WPS every time an object's settings notebook is opened&per.
XFolder overrides this method also to add its own settings
pages, after having called the parent method, so that
the original settings pages are still inserted&per.

:eul.
:p.
The :hp2.XFldDisk:ehp2. class, which replaces the WPDisk class,
does not do much, aside from routing its methods to
the XFolder method counterparts, so that drive views
act just like normal (X)folders&per. IBM has, for some
reason, chosen not to make disk objects regular folders,
but implemented a different class for them (called WPRootFolder),
so XFolder needs a separate class too&per. :hp2.
:p.
XFldObject:ehp2. doesn't do much visibly either, except for
suppressing OS/2 default menu items and adding the "Copy
filename" feature&per. It is however required by other
XFolder parts internally in order to be notified of
some internal WPS events, especially the XShutdown feature,
which is described in detail on the :link reftype=hd res=10128.next page:elink.&per. 
:p.
The :hp2.XFldDesktop:ehp2. class is implemented to allow changing
the Desktop menu items and for XShutdown, which is described
in detail on the :link reftype=hd res=10128.next page:elink.&per. 
:p.
While previous versions also replaced the :hp2.WPSystem:ehp2. class
so that the "System" object in the "System setup" folder
contained more notebook pages to access XFolder's Global
Settings, with V0&per.80 this behavior has changed&per.
Instead, XFolder registers two new classes derived from
WPSystem without replacing it&per. These two classes
are :hp2.XFldSystem:ehp2. and :hp2.XFldWPS:ehp2. for the "OS/2 Kernel" and
"Workplace Shell" objects, respectively&per. The settings
that you specify here are (mostly) stored in OS2&per.INI
and evaluated every time XFolder needs them (e&per.g&per.
when you open a context menu)&per. In contrast, the
"local" XFolder settings for an individual folder are
stored in its &per.CLASSINFO Extended Attributes, where
the WPS also stores the other folder settings&per. This
is then done by the XFolder class&per. 
:p.
Please note that all the XFolder classes are designed
to interact&per. Do not try to remove only SOME of them,
or XFolder might behave in a funny way (if you're lucky)&per.
All of XFolder's features have been made fairly configurable,
so you should be able to get rid of what you don't like
-- or to get rid of XFolder altogether&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "further_2howxshutdown.html"
:h2 res=10128 x=right width=70%.How Does XShutdown Work?
:p.
The XShutdown feature has cost me a lot of thought,
because it is really not documented anywhere what happens
during the normal shutdown process&per. 
:p.
OS/2 per default knows two different shutdown APIs&colon.

:ul compact.:li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DosShutdown:font facename=default size=0x0. only closes all open files, flushes all
file-system buffers und unmounts all file systems; this
is what happens after pressing Ctrl-Alt-Del&per. No
applications are properly closed, and the WPS is not
saved&per. 
.br
:li.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WinShutdownSystem:font facename=default size=0x0. however is the Presentation Manager
API which closes all windows, saves the WPS and finally
calls :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DosShutdown:font facename=default size=0x0.&per. Just the regular shutdown procedure
that you are used to&colon. this is executed when you
select "Shutdown" from the Desktop's context menu or
the respective icons from the Launchpad or WarpCenter&per.

:eul.
:p.
Trouble is, there is no function "in between" these
two&per. If you call :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DosShutdown:font facename=default size=0x0. the WPS data is not
saved&per. And if you call :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WinShutdownSystem:font facename=default size=0x0. you get
the regular shutdown without any further chance to interfere&per.
So basically, I had to recode a complete new :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WinShutdownSystem:font facename=default size=0x0.,
which will now be explained&per. This was quite difficult,
since IBM hardly explains anything about what is really
going on during :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WinShutdownSystem:font facename=default size=0x0.&per. 
:p.
Note&colon. In XWorkplace, the "eXtended Shutdown" and
"Restart Desktop" routines share the same code; they
only differ in what happens after all windows have been
closed&per. I will thus use the term "XShutdown" in
the following explanations for both features, unless
otherwise stated&per. 
:p.
XShutdown is :hp2.integrated into the WPS:ehp2. and relies heavily
on the XWorkplace class replacements&per. I have intentionally
not put the XShutdown code into a separate &per.EXE
file for two reasons&colon. for one, XShutdown needs
access to WPS internal data, which is only available
from the SOM context; second, I want to prevent people
from trying to use XShutdown separately, without having
the XWorkplace classes installed, because this could
severely damage the Workplace Shell&per. In more detail,
XShutdown relies on the XFldObject replacement class
and the XWorkplace Worker thread, which cooperatively
keep track of the WPS internal data&per. 
:p.
To understand what XShutdown is now doing, it is necessary
to understand how the :hp2.WPS handles its objects:ehp2. internally&per.
Every single object which becomes relevant to the WPS
at some point, be it through populating a folder or
querying its settings or starting a program or whatever,
is -- in WPS terminology -- "awakened" by the system,
which means that it exists as a SOM object in memory&per.

:p.
The WPS only very rarely puts awake objects back to
sleep though, which would free the associated memory
and store the object's data back to disk&per. This has
two consequences&colon. 
:ol compact.:li.
There are always many more awakened objects on your
system than you would actually think, because most of
them aren't currently visible&per. Even after you close
an open folder, the objects therein remain awake; this
speeds up populating the folder when it's opened a second
time&per. As a result however, the WPS eats up more
and more of your memory with each folder you open&per.
(If you have turned on the XShutdown log file, you can
see how many awake objects were saved by XShutdown;
these are usually several hundred objects, even though
XShutdown doesn't save all awake objects, but only descendants
of WPFolder and WPAbstract&per. On the "Internals" page
in the Desktop's settings notebook you can take a look
at how many objects are currently awake&per.) 
.br
:li.
A change to the object's data sometimes has only an
effect on the SOM object in memory, but is not always
saved to disk or the OS2&per.INI / OS2SYS&per.INI files&per.
This is why sometimes the WPS gets into trouble if you
make comprehensive changes, such as moving a folder
containing many abstract objects, and do not shutdown
properly&colon. the physical file data on disk and the
WPS records differ then&per. 
:eol.
:p.
This is what XShutdown needs the :hp2.XFldObject:ehp2. class for,
which replaces WPObject&per. Every time an object is
awakened, the WPS calls several methods (among them
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.wpInitData:font facename=default size=0x0. and :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.wpObjectReady:font facename=default size=0x0.)&per. XFldObject overrides
these and passes the object address in memory to the
Worker thread, which will then properly update an XWorkplace-internal
list of all currently awake objects&per. As far as I
know, there is no other way to find out which objects
are currently awake; at least there is no documented
API for enumerating them&per. 
:p.
Now, when :hp2.XShutdown is initiated:ehp2. and confirmed, it first
starts two new threads for the following shutdown procedure,
which run parallel to the regular WPS threads&colon.
the main :hp2."Shutdown thread":ehp2. with the message queue for
the status window, and the :hp2."Update thread",:ehp2. which monitors
the OS/2 Window List and posts messages to the main
shutdown thread, if the status window needs to be updated&per.
So closing all currently open windows is a fairly complex
process of interaction between these two threads&colon.
the Shutdown thread closes a window and then goes to
sleep until the Update thread has detected a change
in the Window List (which means that the window has
successfully been closed) and posts a message back to
the Shutdown thread, which then in turn closes the next
window, until all windows are closed&per. 
:p.
When all windows are closed, the Update thread exits&per.
Now the Shutdown thread goes through the list of currently
awake objects (which was described above) and forces
saving their data to the INI files or to disk by calling
each object's :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.wpSaveImmediate:font facename=default size=0x0. method&per. This is only
done for WPAbstract and WPFolder descendants, because
from my experience, all other classes save their data
synchroneously&per. (I have tried saving all WPFileSystem
descendants once, and this caused a lot of extended
attributes to be created for every single file that
was ever awakened by the WPS&per. In addition, shutdown
took ages then&per.) 
:p.
Finally, depending on what action was desired, the Shutdown
thread does one of the following&colon. 
:ul compact.:li.
If you selected :hp2."Restart Desktop",:ehp2. the Shutdown thread
simply executes :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DosExit(EXIT_PROCESS, 0):font facename=default size=0x0.&per. Since
XWorkplace is part of the Workplace process, and all
parts of the WPS are running in this one process (the
second instance of :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.PMSHELL&per.EXE:font facename=default size=0x0.), this will terminate
the whole Workplace Shell&per. The Shell process (the
first instance of :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.PMSHELL&per.EXE:font facename=default size=0x0.) will then restart
the WPS automatically&per. 
.br
:li.
If you selected "Shutdown" and :hp2."Reboot afterwards",:ehp2.
XShutdown now also saves the INI files to disk&per.
This is necessary, because :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DosShutdown,:font facename=default size=0x0. which is called
afterwards, does not save them either&per. (I guess
it's because the INI file API's belong to Presentation
Manager&per.) Since the PM INI file API's prohibit simply
closing the user and system profiles (which does write
their data to disk for all other profiles), XWorkplace
copies them to two temporary profiles, deletes the originals,
and then renames the temporary profiles to the names
of the originals&per. After :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DosShutdown:font facename=default size=0x0. ("Releasing
file systems&per.&per.&per."), the system is rebooted
via a call to the DOS&per.SYS device driver&per. This
feature is documented in :link reftype=hd res=10153.EDM/2:elink. volume 5, issue 9&per.

.br
:li.
If you selected "Shutdown" and :hp2.NOT "Reboot afterwards",:ehp2.
after :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DosShutdown,:font facename=default size=0x0. XShutdown disables the window list
and then simply blocks the system by calling :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DosEnterCritSec:font facename=default size=0x0.
and staying in an infinite loop&per. Since all file
systems are closed, no further action should be possible,
except for turning off your computer or pressing Ctrl-Alt-Del&per.

:eul.
:p.

.* Source file: "further_2howxtrash.html"
:h2 res=10129 x=right width=70%.How Does the Trash Can Work?
:p.
Even though the trash can looks like a normal folder,
it behaves quite differently internally&per. 
:ul compact.:li.
When an :hp2.object is deleted:ehp2. into the trash can (either
by dropping it onto the trash can or by selecting "Delete"
from the object's context menu), it is :hp1.not:ehp1. physically
moved into the trash can folder (which, being a folder,
is a regular directory on the disk)&per. 
:p.
Instead, the following happens&colon. 
.br

:ol compact.:li.
The trash can then creates an invisible directory in
the root directory of the drive where the object resides&per.
This directory is always called :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.\TRASH:font facename=default size=0x0.&per. (You can
see it by typing :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DIR /A \:font facename=default size=0x0. on the command line&per.)

.br
:li.
The trash can then creates a subpath in that hidden
directory according to the path where the object currently
resides&per. That is, for example, if the object is
in the folder :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.D&colon.\MYFILES\ARTICLES:font facename=default size=0x0., the directory
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.D&colon.\TRASH\MYFILES\ARTICLES:font facename=default size=0x0. is created&per. This
allows the trash can to remember where the object was
deleted from&per. 
.br
:li.
The object is then moved into :hp1.that:ehp1. directory (and not
the actual trash can folder)&per. 
:p.
The reason for this is simple&colon. speed&per. If we
were physically moving objects into the trash can folder,
this would frequently move files across drives&per.
(Just think about moving a 30 MB file into the trash
can this way&per.) By contrast, since the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.\TRASH:font facename=default size=0x0. directory
is always on the same drive as the object, even moving
large folder trees should take place very fast&per.

.br
:li.
In order to still make the object visible in the trash
can itself, an instance of XWPTrashObject is created
in the trash can&per. This class is a subclass of WPTransient,
which means that it is not persistent between Desktop
restarts, but only while the WPS is running&per. As
a result, these "trash objects" do not consume any space
in OS2&per.INI&per. 
:p.
So when an object is moved to the trash can, it is actually
duplicated&colon. the "real" object is moved to the
invisible :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.\TRASH:font facename=default size=0x0. directory tree, and a "trash object"
(XFldTrashObject, WPTransient subclass) is created in
the trash can&per. 
:eol.
:p.

.br
:li.
When the :hp2.trash can is opened:ehp2. (and thus populated), all
drives are scanned for the hidden :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.\TRASH:font facename=default size=0x0. directories,
and trash objects are created according to the objects
which reside in the subdirectories in there&per. 
.br
:li.
When an :hp2.object is restored:ehp2. (or moved out of the trash
can), the corresponding "real" object in the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.\TRASH:font facename=default size=0x0.
directories is moved back to where it was deleted from
(or to the location where the user is moving it to),
and the trash object in the trash can is destroyed,
since it serves no longer any purpose&per. 
.br
:li.
When an :hp2.object is destroyed:ehp2. (or the trash can is emptied
altogether), all objects in the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.\TRASH:font facename=default size=0x0. directories are
destroyed, and all trash objects in the trash can are
destroyed also&per. 
:eul.
:p.
This approach seemed like a good compromise for speed
and stability, while not messing with the WPS internals
too much&per. I had initially thought about using a
subclass of WPAbstract for the trash can, but this would
create lots of entries in OS2&per.INI with the usual
problems associated with that&per. 
:p.
Besides, using a subclass of WPTransient has another
advantage&per. Since the trash objects (the transient
objects) are recreated from scratch after every WPS
restart, if something goes wrong really bad, you can
manually delete all the hidden :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.\TRASH:font facename=default size=0x0. directories on
all drives, and after the next Desktop startup, the
trash can is completely empty&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "further_2howxx1_hook.html"
:h2 res=10130 x=right width=70%.How Does the XWorkplace PM Hook work?
:p.
In general, a Presentation Manager (PM) hook is a piece
of code which is registered with PM to receive all messages
which are going through the system&per. As a result,
that piece of code effectively becomes part of every
process on the system which is processing messages&per.

:p.
With PM (and Windows too), windows communicate with
:hp2.messages&per.:ehp2. The system sends messages to windows automatically
for all kinds of events, and windows can send messages
to each other as well&per. There are hundreds of different
system messages, and application can define their own
messages too&per. 
:p.
For example, if you click on any window with the left
mouse button, that window is sent the the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_BUTTON1CLICK:font facename=default size=0x0.
message by the system&per. What happens then depends
on the type (in PM&colon. the class) of the window&per.
For example, a container control will look if there's
a container record under the mouse pointer and, if so,
select the corresponding record&per. A Netscape client
window will see if there's a link under the mouse pointer
and, if so, load a new HTML page to follow the link&per.

:p.
There are many more "important" system messages, such
as :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_CHAR:font facename=default size=0x0. (for keystrokes), :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_SIZE:font facename=default size=0x0. (when windows are
resized), :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_PAINT:font facename=default size=0x0. (when windows need repainting), and
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_DESTROY:font facename=default size=0x0. (when windows are destroyed)&per. That's
basically why PM programming seems so complicated at
first, because PM programming mostly means reacting
to messages, which is quite different from "regular"
programming, where programs are normally simply processing
tasks sequentially&per. With PM, if no messages are
queued for a window, a program normally simply does
nothing&per. Its threads are blocked until messages
come in&per. 
:p.
Now, when a :hp2.global message hook function:ehp2. is registered
with the system, all messages go through that hook function
:hp1.before:ehp1. the target window receives that message&per.
This way a hook function can choose to modify the message,
redirect it to a different window, do something completely
different itself, or even swallow the message so that
the target window won't receive it&per. 
:p.
This is how all the well-known PM hook utilities (such
NPS WPS, FeelX, ProgramCommander/2, X-it, Styler/2,
and the XWorkplace PM hook as well) work&per. They intercept
certain messages and manipulate them&per. 
:p.
For example, every time the XWorkplace PM hook encounters
a :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_CHAR:font facename=default size=0x0. message (that is, when a key on the keyboard
is pressed or released), it will check if that key is
on the global hotkeys list&per. If so, the message is
swallowed (so that the target window won't receive it)
and some part of the XWorkplace WPS code is notified
instead, which can then open the corresponding object
which has been defined by the user for that hotkey&per.

:p.
The way the XWorkplace hook is implemented differs slightly
from that of the typical hook utilities&per. Most of
those utilities register their hook function with PM
when they are started and de-register the hook again
when the program is ended (for example, if "close" is
chosen from the window list)&per. 
:p.
Instead, XWorkplace's PM hook is registered from a special
program which is not visible in the window list -- the
:hp2.XWorkplace daemon,:ehp2. :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XWPDAEMN&per.EXE:font facename=default size=0x0.&per. You can see
it with WatchCat or any other process lister though&per.
Try killing that program&colon. you will see that all
hook functionality will be gone&per. :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.
:p.
XWPDAEMN&per.EXE:font facename=default size=0x0. is started by XWorkplace while the
WPS is starting up for the first time and keeps running
until the system is shut down&per. That is, the daemon
even keeps running between Desktop restarts&per. 
:p.
Even though the daemon is a PM program, it doesn't create
any windows (except for the XPager window, see below)&per.

:p.
All this is pretty complex in detail because this involves
using shared memory and proper serialization techniques
such as shared mutex semaphores and cross-process messaging,
especially since the hook is configured from WPS settings
pages, which are running in the WPS process&per. But
I hope you get the basic idea&per. 
:p.
There are a number of good reasons why I chose that
approach&colon. 
:ol compact.:li.
It's usually not a good idea to start hooks from the
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.PMSHELL&per.EXE:font facename=default size=0x0. process, which all WPS classes are running
in&per. If the WPS crashes, it's more difficult to clean
up installed hooks because the WPS is so complex in
itself&per. 
.br
:li.
Since the daemon keeps running between Desktop restarts,
it can also keep track of certain data which is needed
between Desktop restarts&per. For example, the XWorkplace
startup folder shouldn't be processed again when the
WPS is restarted (unless the user requests this)&per.
Try it out&colon. If you kill the daemon and then restart
the WPS, you'll see that the XWorkplace startup folder
will get processed again, because the XWorkplace WPS
classes see that the daemon is not running and then
think that the WPS is starting up for the first time&per.

.br
:li.
XPager is part of the daemon as well and is thus independent
of the WPS&per. XPager requires lots of message monitoring
as well since it needs to know about window creation
and destruction&per. At any point in time, XPager knows
about every single window on the system&per. It's much
easier for XPager to keep its own windows apart from
the rest of the system when it's running in a separate
process&per. 
:p.
For details about XPager, see :link reftype=hd res=10080."How it works":elink. in the
:link reftype=hd res=10010.XPager section&per.:elink. 
:eol.
:p.

.* Source file: "further_3develop.html"
:h2 res=10131 x=right width=70%.How Was XWorkplace Developed?
:p.
XWorkplace is programmed in C, using the Warp 3 Developer's
Toolkit&per. All XFolder versions until 0&per.72 were
programmed using the IBM C-Set/2 compiler&per. Thanks
to the generous support of Mark Mellin, who sent me
VisualAge C++ 3&per.0, all versions from XFolder 0&per.80
(that is, XWorkplace too) will have been compiled using
that compiler, which has a number of helpful improvements
over the earlier IBM compilers&per. 
:p.
I got my C-Set/2 from the German OS/2 magazine "OS/2
Inside", which was said to be the best OS/2 printing
in the world&per. They had a CD-ROM for just some US-$
20, containing a full C-Set&per. 
:p.
I used to have the ordering address on this page, but
"OS/2 Inside" has gone out of business, and their ordering
shop has reportedly been closed down also&per. So sadly,
I know no way to obtain a cheap IBM compiler for OS/2
any more&per. 
:p.
It is still possible to write WPS classes using the
great free EMX/GCC compiler, which is available for
download at :link reftype=hd res=10172.LEO:elink. in Germany&per. The only requirement
is a Warp 3 Developer's Toolkit, unfortunately&per.

:p.
While IBM has stated that it will no longer support
SOM altoghether, it is still a great technology, although
it needs quite a bit of reading until you know what's
going on&per. 
:p.
The Warp 3 Toolkit contains everything for developing
powerful WPS classes&per. It is sufficiently documented
to understand the basic WPS functionality, enabling
me (who neither knew C nor the OS/2 API, but only OOP
with Pascal and Windows 3&per.1) to build XFolder's
basic functionality (version 0&per.11) in a triplet
of days&per. (Things become more difficult with more
sophisticated features, but that's another story&per.)

:p.
Valuable reading, aside from the Toolkit docs, can also
be found in the four IBM OS/2 V2&per.0 Redbooks, which
I found on an old Hobbes CD-ROM and which are still
available on the commonly known FTP sites&per. It is
quite outdated (dealing only with OS/2 V2&per.0), but
the system's basic concepts have pretty much remained
the same&per. 
:p.
I also strongly recommend the :link reftype=hd res=10153.Electronic Developer's
Magazine for OS/2:elink. on the WWW, which has published fabulous
articles on all aspects of OS/2 programming&per. There
are two series about WPS programming, one starting in
volume 2 issue 8, the other one in volume 5 issue 10&per.

:p.
If you have the above tools, you should be able to program
the WPS in a jiffy&per. All you still need then is a
good portion of patience, since the WPS runs in a single
process (PMSHELL&per.EXE), and bugs in your project
will make the whole thing crash repeatedly&per. Check
the helpful "Debugging WPS applications" section in
the Toolkit WPS Guide to compensate at least the most
annoying problems&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "further_4personal.html"
