.* Source file: "plug_1intro.html"
:h2 res=10133 x=right width=70%.Introduction
:p.
The XCenter supports widget plug-in DLLs&per. To the
XCenter, it doesn't matter whether a widget class is
built into :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XFLDR&per.DLL:font facename=default size=0x0. itself or implemented externally
through a plug-in DLL&per. See :link reftype=hd res=10094."About plug-in DLLs":elink.
for a general introduction to this feature of the XCenter&per.

:p.
The existing :link reftype=hd res=10093.standard widget classes:elink. are partly built
into :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XFLDR&per.DLL:font facename=default size=0x0. itself (if they make extensive use
of WPS features, such as with the object button widget),
but some of them are already implemented as plug-in
DLLs&per. This was done for two reasons&colon. first,
to test that the plug-in DLL interface actually works,
and second, to give potential developers the chance
to look at how this can be done&per. 
:p.
Please read through the :link reftype=hd res=10135.Terminology:elink. section first to
make sure you know about the wording used here&per.

:p.
Then, basically, you can start with the minimal widget
which comes with the XWorkplace binary release&per.
In this case, you do not even need the XWorkplace source
code&per. All you need is the XCenter include file,
which now comes with XWorkplace (see :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.toolkit\center&per.h:font facename=default size=0x0.)&per.

:p.
See :link reftype=hd res=10136.Step 1&colon. One header only:elink. for an introduction,
which gets more complicated with the following steps&per.

.br

.* Source file: "plug_1require.html"
:h2 res=10134 x=right width=70%.Requirements
:p.
To write a plug-in DLL, you need to be familiar with
the following&colon. 
:ol compact.:li.
The C programming language&per. There is no language
support for the OS/2 Pascal dialects at this point&per.

.br
:li.
Presentation Manager programming&per. A widget class
is essentially a PM window class (see :link reftype=hd res=10135."Terminology":elink.)&per.

:p.
If you haven't written a PM window class from scratch
before, don't worry&per. The samples will guide you,
and it isn't that difficult&per. If you know what a
window procedure is, and if you know the difference
between an owner and a parent window and :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WinSendMsg:font facename=default size=0x0.
and :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WinPostMsg:font facename=default size=0x0., you should be fine&per. Of course, the
more you know, the better&per. 
.br
:li.
You should know what a DLL is, when and why they are
used, and why a DLL is not a process&per. ;-) 
:eol.
:p.
Now for the good news&colon. You do :hp1.not:ehp1. need to know
WPS and/or SOM programming, which should be a great
relief to many contributors&per. 
:p.
Also, you can use any C compiler you want&per. Even
EMX/GCC should do&per. The only XWorkplace code that
is required are the headers that you are including,
which now come with the XWorkplace binary distribution
(in the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.toolkit:font facename=default size=0x0. directory)&per. 
:p.
If you get lost, you can always download the :link reftype=hd res=10026.complete
XWorkplace source code:elink., where you will find the source
code for the standard plug-in DLLs which come with XWorkplace
(the window list and the clock and memory monitors),
which show you in detail how it's done&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "plug_2terminology.html"
:h2 res=10135 x=right width=70%.Terminology
:p.
The following terms are used throughout this documentation,
and you should therefore be familiar with these&per.

:ul compact.:li.
An :hp2."XCenter instance":ehp2. is an object of the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XCenter:font facename=default size=0x0. WPS
class&per. There can only be one open view per XCenter
so that an XCenter instance is identical to an XCenter
view when it's open, but there can be several XCenter
instances on the system (i&per.e&per. one for each screen
border)&per. 
:p.
Even though the XCenter itself is obviously a Desktop
object, it completely isolates the widgets from the
WPS stuff internally&per. This is why SOM/WPS programming
knowledge is not required to write a new widget class,
but you can still do WPS programming if you want to&per.

.br
:li.
A :hp2."widget":ehp2. is a PM subwindow of an open XCenter which
displays something&per. An open XCenter can contain
zero, one, or many widgets&per. Every XCenter keeps
a list of widgets together with their settings in its
SOM instance data&per. This is totally transparent to
the widgets, but if you are interested, you can view
that data on the "Widgets" page of an XCenter's settings
notebook&per. 
:p.
Again, to make that clear&colon. A widget is a separate
PM window inside the XCenter&per. 
.br
:li.
A :hp2."widget class":ehp2. defines a widget&per. Basically, it's
a PM window class with a plain C structure as a wrapper
(:link reftype=hd res=10144.:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XCENTERWIDGETCLASS:font facename=default size=0x0.:elink.)&per. This structure holds the name
of a PM window class which is used by the XCenter to
create the PM widget windows&per. Depending on the widget
class's attributes, there can be one or several instances
of a widget class&per. If you want a different widget
in the XCenter, you need to write a widget class&per.

:p.
Writing a widget class basically boils down to writing
a PM window class (see below), with some additional
rules to follow&per. To make things easier, several
widget classes can share the same PM class though&per.

:p.
Some widget classes are built into the XCenter itself
(i&per.e&per. reside in :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XFLDR&per.DLL:font facename=default size=0x0.), but the XCenter
can obviously load external plug-in DLLs too&per. Several
of the widget classes that come with XWorkplace have
been created as plug-ins to show you how it's done&per.
If you have the :link reftype=hd res=10026.XWorkplace source code:elink., look for the
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.src\widgets:font facename=default size=0x0. directory&per. 
.br
:li.
A :hp2."PM window class":ehp2. is not an XCenter definition&per.&per.&per.
this is explained in detail in the :hp1.Presentation Manager
Programming Reference&per.:ehp1. 
:p.
Basically, PM organizes windows into classes&per. For
example, if you create a PM button, you invoke :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WinCreateWindow:font facename=default size=0x0.
with the name of the button window class (:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WC_BUTTON:font facename=default size=0x0.),
which is a standard window class of every OS/2 system&per.

:p.
It is possible to create new window classes though&per.
The XCenter makes use of this feature to implement widget
classes&per. So again, a widget class is a PM window
class with a bit of extra data to give the XCenter more
information about the widgets that can be created of
that class&per. 
:p.
The advantage of using separate PM window classes is
that a widget is essentially free to do whatever it
wants&per. It can say "Hello world", but it can also
choose to start a dozen subthreads with videos playing&per.

:p.
The disadvantage is that writing a PM window class from
scratch is a bit more difficult than using standard
controls&per. But that's why there are plenty of samples
to learn from&per. 
:p.
When a widget is created (either because it is added
to an open XCenter or when an XCenter is opened in the
first place and thus all widgets have to be created),
it does call :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WinCreateWindow:font facename=default size=0x0. with the PM window class
name that was specified with the widget class&per. So
this is really not too spectacular&per. 
.br
:li.
A :hp2."widget plugin DLL":ehp2. is a separate DLL which resides
in the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.plugins\xcenter:font facename=default size=0x0. directory of the XWorkplace installation
directory&per. This must contain one or several widget
classes&per. There are three procedures that a widget
plugin DLL is required to export to make the XCenter
see the widget classes&per. This is explained in detail
on the next pages&per. 
:eul.
:p.

.* Source file: "plug_51simple.html"
:h2 res=10136 x=right width=70%.Step 1: One Header Only
:p.
XWorkplace now comes with a mini-widget sample (:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.toolkit\miniwdgt&per.c:font facename=default size=0x0.)
which contains an absolute minimum widget without any
fancy functionality&per. All this widget does is display
a question mark&per. 
:p.
This mini widget was added to show you something to
start with&per. It can definitely be improved&per. It
does :hp1.not:ehp1. 
:ul compact.:li.
store any settings (not even font or color presentation
parameters -- see :link reftype=hd res=10137.step 2:elink. for this); 
.br
:li.
display tooltips (fly-over help -- see :link reftype=hd res=10138.step 3:elink. for this);

.br
:li.
implement a settings dialog (see :link reftype=hd res=10140.step 4:elink. for this); 
:eul.
:p.
At the very least, a plug-in DLL must do the following&colon.

:ol compact.:li.
It must :hp2.export three procedures:ehp2. by ordinal&per. :hp2.
:p.
a):ehp2. The :hp2."init":ehp2. export (ordinal 1) gets called once only
by the XCenter when your DLL gets loaded&per. The DLL
can get loaded in situations other than widget creation,
so do not expect this to always be the case&per. On
init, the DLL should register the widget's PM window
class (by calling :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WinRegisterClass:font facename=default size=0x0.)&per. In addition,
it can import functions from :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XFLDR&per.DLL:font facename=default size=0x0., whose module
handle is given to it (this is optional)&per. However,
it must always return a pointer to the array of :link reftype=hd res=10144.:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XCENTERWIDGETCLASS:font facename=default size=0x0.:elink.
structures in the DLL so that the XCenter knows about
the classes in the DLL&per. 
:p.
See :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.toolkit\miniwdgt&per.c:font facename=default size=0x0. for how this is done&per.
:hp2.
:p.
b):ehp2. The :hp2."uninit":ehp2. export (ordinal 2) gets called when
the DLL is unloaded by the XCenter&per. This can do
cleanup, if necessary&per. :hp2.
:p.
c):ehp2. The :hp2."query version":ehp2. export (ordinal 3) gets called
even before the "init" export to check the XWorkplace
version number that this widget requires&per. 
.br
:li.
The plug-in DLL must then contain a :hp2.PM window procedure:ehp2.
for the widget class&per. In the mini widget sample,
this is the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.fnwpSampleWidget:font facename=default size=0x0. procedure&per. The "Init"
export is reponsible for calling :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WinRegisterClass:font facename=default size=0x0. on
that window procedure to create a PM window class from
it&per. 
:p.
This is the usual switch/case stuff that is used with
every PM window procedure&per. There are a couple of
extra considerations to be made though, which are explained
below&per. 
.br
:li.
On :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_CREATE:font facename=default size=0x0., the widget :hp1.must:ehp1. store the :link reftype=hd res=10143.:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XCENTERWIDGET:font facename=default size=0x0.:elink.
pointer it receives with :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.mp1:font facename=default size=0x0. in its :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.QWL_USER:font facename=default size=0x0. window
word&per. That's why the mini widget sample calls :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WinSetWindowPtr(hwnd,
QWL_USER, mp1);:font facename=default size=0x0. on WM_CREATE&per. 
.br
:li.
On :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_CONTROL:font facename=default size=0x0., it should handle notifications from the
XCenter&per. The XCenter will send :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_CONTROL:font facename=default size=0x0. messages
to the widget when it wants to know the widget's size,
for example&per. 
:p.
The notification codes that the XCenter uses with :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_CONTROL:font facename=default size=0x0.
are listed in :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.toolkit\center&per.h:font facename=default size=0x0.&per. There will probably
be more of them in the future&per. 
.br
:li.
Normally, with PM, all unprocessed messages are forwarded
to :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WinDefWindowProc:font facename=default size=0x0.&per. With widgets, this is different&colon.
you must always pass unprocessed messages to the "XCenter
default widget procedure", whose address is given to
your widget in the :link reftype=hd res=10143.:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XCENTERWIDGET:font facename=default size=0x0.:elink. structure on :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_CREATE:font facename=default size=0x0.
in the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.pfnwpDefWidgetProc:font facename=default size=0x0. field&per. (Yes, this is the
reason why you must store that structure in your window
words&per.) 
:p.
If you do not pass unused messages on, you will severely
hurt the widget's functionality&per. Even worse, you
will cause memory leaks because the default widget procedure
is responsible for cleaning up resources and important
XCenter notifications&per. 
.br
:li.
Even if you do your own processing on :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_DESTROY:font facename=default size=0x0., you
must :hp1.always, always:ehp1. pass :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_DESTROY:font facename=default size=0x0. on to :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.pfnwpDefWidgetProc:font facename=default size=0x0.&per.
Otherwise the XCenter cannot clean up your widget's
resources properly&per. 
:eol.
:p.

.* Source file: "plug_52strings.html"
:h2 res=10137 x=right width=70%.Step 2: Supporting Setup Strings
:p.
OK, so your minimal widget from step 1 is running&per.

:p.
You probably have figured out already that even though
the minimal widget does react to fonts and colors dropped
on it, those fonts and colors are not saved when the
XCenter is closed and then re-opened&per. 
:p.
Similarly, if you changed the minimal widget to be sizeable
(by setting the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WGTF_SIZEABLE:font facename=default size=0x0. flag in the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.ulClassFlags:font facename=default size=0x0.
field of :link reftype=hd res=10144.:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XCENTERWIDGETCLASS:font facename=default size=0x0.:elink., you will find out that
the widget's size will not be remembered either&per.

:p.
Of course, the XCenter could have implemented saving
these settings for your widget&per. But then, where
would your widget store additional data that the XCenter
would not know of? Using the profile functions to store
the widget data in :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.OS2&per.INI:font facename=default size=0x0. would not be a good idea
because there can be several instances of your widget,
which should all store their data independently&per.

:p.
As a result, I figured that storing widgets data together
with the data of the XCenter that the widget belongs
to would be the best idea&per. 
:p.
To make this most flexible and easy to use, the widgets
can have :hp2.setup strings:ehp2. associated with them&per. If
you look at the "Widgets" page in the properties notebook
of an XCenter, you will see that each widget can have
its own setup string to store any data it wants&per.

:p.
Even though the widgets are not Desktop objects themselves,
for simplicity, I chose to use the WPS setup string
format for the widgets also&per. That is, your widget
can understand, for example, a :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.BACKGROUNDCOLOR=00FF00;:font facename=default size=0x0.
setup string, which would set the widget's background
color to green&per. 
:p.
Your widget class must now implement two things&colon.

:ul compact.:li.
:hp2.Parse a setup string:ehp2. and convert it into binary data
that your widget can use&per. In the above example,
for the background color, you could say that the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.BACKGROUNDCOLOR:font facename=default size=0x0.
string would have to be followed by a six-digit RGB
hex value&per. The definition is up to your widget class&per.

.br
:li.
:hp2.Create a setup string:ehp2. from a set of binary values&per.
This is needed when the data of your widget is about
to be saved&per. 
:eul.
:p.
When your widget is created, it receives a previously
stored setup string in the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.pcszSetupString:font facename=default size=0x0. field of
its :link reftype=hd res=10143.:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XCENTERWIDGET:font facename=default size=0x0.:elink. structure that comes with :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_CREATE:font facename=default size=0x0.&per.
You can then allocate your own structure and store it
in :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XCENTERWIDGET&per.pUser:font facename=default size=0x0., parse the setup string,
and store the values in there&per. Of course, you should
set up safe defaults if a setup string is missing because
there won't be any when your widget is initially created
by the user&per. 
:p.
Reversely, when your widget's data has changed (e&per.g&per.
because a new background color has been dropped on it),
it should compose a new full setup string&per. After
the new setup string is composed, the widget must send
the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XCM_SAVESETUP:font facename=default size=0x0. message to its parent window (which
is either the XCenter client or a tray widget window,
if the widget resides in a tray), which will cause the
new setup string to be stored together with the other
widget data in the XCenter's private data&per. See :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.center&per.h:font facename=default size=0x0.
for details&per. 
:p.
In order to encapsulate the setup string functionality,
I recommend that you create a new structure definition
for "saveable instance data"&per. This could, for example,
contain fields for background, foreground color, and
font to be used&per. For sizeable widgets, this could
also include the current size&per. 
:p.
This encapsulation allows your widget class to work
on setup strings with setup dialogs later also, which
can even be invoked when no instance of your widget
presently exists&per. 
:p.
The minimal sample has no provisions for setup strings&per.
Download the XWorkplace source code and look into the
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.src\widgets:font facename=default size=0x0. directory, which has more examples for how
this works&per. :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XFLDR&per.DLL:font facename=default size=0x0. also exports a couple
of handy functions that you can use to parse setup strings
more easily&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "plug_53tooltips.html"
:h2 res=10138 x=right width=70%.Step 3: Adding Tooltips
:p.
To make your widget support tooltips (fly-over help),
set the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WGTF_TOOLTIP:font facename=default size=0x0. flag in the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.ulClassFlags:font facename=default size=0x0. field
of :link reftype=hd res=10144.:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XCENTERWIDGETCLASS:font facename=default size=0x0.:elink.&per. 
:p.
Only if that bit is set, your widget will receive a
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WM_CONTROL:font facename=default size=0x0. message with the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.TTN_NEEDTEXT:font facename=default size=0x0. notification
and :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XCENTER_TOOLTIP:font facename=default size=0x0. as the control's ID&per. 
:p.
You will need to include :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.include\helpers\comctl&per.h:font facename=default size=0x0.
from the XWorkplace helpers for the definitions of the
XWorkplace tooltip control&per. 
:p.
Again, if you have the full XWorkplace source code,
see the widgets in :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.src\widgets:font facename=default size=0x0. for how this is done&per.

.br

.* Source file: "plug_54imports.html"
:h2 res=10139 x=right width=70%.Step 4: Importing functions from XFLDR.DLL
:p.
As you might imagine, there is plenty of useful code
in :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XFLDR&per.DLL:font facename=default size=0x0. -- for graphics, strings, PM controls,
and much more&per. Most of what you see in the "XWorkplace
helpers" sources is probably in :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XFLDR&per.DLL:font facename=default size=0x0. somewhere&per.

:p.
Now, if you want to use that code, you basically have
two options&per. 
:ol compact.:li.
Copy and paste the functions from the helpers sources
(or wherever else from) into your widget code&per. 
.br
:li.
The smart way to do this however would be to avoid duplicate
code and use the code from :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XFLDR&per.DLL:font facename=default size=0x0.&per. The XCenter
interfaces allow you to do exactly that&colon. 
:p.
When your DLL's "init" export gets called (ordinal 1),
it receives the module handle of :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XFLDR&per.DLL:font facename=default size=0x0.&per.
You can then use :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.DosQueryProcAddr:font facename=default size=0x0. to resolve the addresses
of functions which are exported from :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XFLDR&per.DLL:font facename=default size=0x0.,
store those function pointers in global variables, and
use them instead&per. 
:p.
Again, see the standard widgets in :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.src\widgets\:font facename=default size=0x0. in the
XWorkplace sources, which all make use of this feature&per.

:p.
To make sure the prototypes are correct, many prototypes
have already been typedef'd in the various XWorkplace
header files&per. Basically, I added a typedef whenever
I needed an export myself&per. Similarly, in :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.src\shared\xwp&per.def:font facename=default size=0x0.,
you will find those functions exported which I needed
for the standard plugins&per. If you need more functions
and prototypes, just contact me, and I'll add them&per.

:eol.
:p.

.* Source file: "plug_55dialog.html"
:h2 res=10140 x=right width=70%.Step 5: Settings Dialogs
:p.
Settings dialogs can be displayed by the XCenter to
further tune the instance data of a certain widget&per.
An example of a settings dialog is the "Filter" dialog
displayed by the standard "Window List" widget that
comes with XWorkplace&per. 
:p.
Using settings dialogs requires a bit more setup&per.
The most important thing to remember is that the XCenter
does :hp1.not:ehp1. invoke a settings dialog on an open XCenter
widget, but on a :hp1.setup string:ehp1. only&per. 
:p.
This was done so that settings dialogs can be displayed
for a widget even if that widget is not currently visible
(i&per.e&per. doesn't currently exist as a window)&per.
This allows the XCenter to display the settings dialog
from both the "Properties" menu item in a widget's context
menu and from a widget's context menu on the "Widgets"
page in the XCenter settings notebook -- even if the
XCenter isn't currently open&per. 
:p.
Basically, to support settings dialogs, your widget
class must do the following&colon. 
:ol compact.:li.
In the widget class definition (:link reftype=hd res=10144.:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.XCENTERWIDGETCLASS:font facename=default size=0x0.:elink.),
set the :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.pShowSettingsDlg:font facename=default size=0x0. field to the function in your
DLL which can display the settings dialog&per. 
:p.
This function must have the following prototype&colon.
:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.
:p.
typedef VOID EXPENTRY ShowSettingsDialog(PWIDGETSETTINGSDLGDATA
pData);:font facename=default size=0x0. 
.br
:li.
When the XCenter needs to invoke the settings dialog
(e&per.g&per. because the "Properties" menu item was
selected), it will call exactly this function, which
should do a standard :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WinDlgBox:font facename=default size=0x0. and not return until
the dialog has been dismissed ("OK" or "Cancel" were
pressed)&per. 
:p.
That function receives a pointer to a temporary :link reftype=hd res=10141.:font facename='Courier' size=18x12.WIDGETSETTINGSDLGDATA:font facename=default size=0x0.:elink.
structure, which the XCenter has composed for the settings
dialog&per. In there, the settings dialog can find out
whether the widget is currently visible&per. 
:eol.
:p.
For details, please look at the "Window list" source
code in :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.src\widgets:font facename=default size=0x0. in the XWorkplace sources&per. 
.br

.* Source file: "plug_9widgetsettingsdlgdata.html"
:h2 res=10141 x=right width=70%.WIDGETSETTINGSDLGDATA
:p.
:hp2.Note&colon.:ehp2. This is an excerpt from :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.center&per.h:font facename=default size=0x0.&per.
This definition is not necessarily up-to-date&per. Always
use :font facename='Courier' size=18x12.center&per.h:font facename=default size=0x0. in your widget source code instead
of this definition&per. 
:cgraphic.
  /*
   *@@ WIDGETSETTINGSDLGDATA&colon.
   *      a bunch of data passed to a "show settings
   *      dialog" function (WGTSHOWSETTINGSDLG), if
   *      the widget has specified such a thing&per.
   *
   *      XCenter widget settings dialogs basically
   *      work as follows&colon.
   *
   *      1&per.  You must a function that displays a modal
   *          dialog&per. This function must have the following
   *          prototype&colon.
   *
   +              VOID EXPENTRY ShowSettingsDlg(PWIDGETSETTINGSDLGDATA pData)
   *
   *      2&per.  Store that function in the
   *          XCENTERWIDGETCLASS&per.pShowSettingsDlg field for
   *          your widget class&per.
   *
   *          This will enable the "Properties" menu item
   *          for the widget&per.
   *
   *      3&per.  Your function gets called when the user selects
   *          "Properties"&per. What that function does, doesn't
   *          matter&per.&per.&per. it should however display a modal
   *          dialog and update the widget's settings string
   *          and call ctrSetSetupString with the "hSettings"
   *          handle that was given to it in the
   *          WIDGETSETTINGSDLGDATA structure&per. This will give
   *          the widget the new settings&per.
   *
   *          The address of the ctrSetSetupString helper is
   *          given to you in this structure so that you
   *          won't have to import it from XFLDR&per.DLL&per.
   *
   *      If a widget class supports settings dialogs,
   *      it must specify this in its XCENTERWIDGETCLASS&per.
   *
   *@@added V0&per.9&per.7 (2000-12-07) [umoeller]
   *@@changed V0&per.9&per.9 (2001-02-06) [umoeller]&colon. added pctrSetSetupString
   */

  typedef struct _WIDGETSETTINGSDLGDATA
  {
      HWND                    hwndOwner;
                  // proposed owner for settings dialog

      const char              *pcszSetupString;
                  // present setup string (do not change)

      const LHANDLE           hSettings;
